<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges Search for Peace in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony Blair
pledged today to continue the search for peace in Northern Ireland
despite violence there over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
"I am not going to give up on Northern Ireland. I am going to
carry on searching for a solution and I believe if there were true
good will on all sides and a little bit of give and take and
understanding a solution could be found," Blair said in a speech
to parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent violence in Northern Ireland had been
appalling and appealed to the two rival ethnic groups--the
Protestants and Roman Catholics-- to do everything they could to
keep the drive for peace on course.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, fresh from the NATO summit in Madrid, also
backed Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam for her attempts to
avert conflict, saying she had negotiated in good faith and
praising her for her "courage and determination."
</P>
<P>
Mowlam has been bitterly criticized by the nationalist
community for allowing a Protestant Orange Order parade go ahead
on Sunday through a predominantly Roman Catholic area of
Portadown, which led to several-day serious riot unseen for years.
</P>
<P>
Criticism of Mowlam has been intensified by the publication of
a leaked document which appeared to show the decision to allow the
Portadown march through had been taken well before negotiations
between the two sides. Mowlam has ordered an investigation into
the leak.
</P>
<P>
The government has dismissed the reports, saying the document
was merely an initial review of options.
</P>
<P>
But this has failed to stem the criticism of Mowlam, who
condemned the riots today and told parliament that progress
towards peace could only be made through "accommodation and
negotiation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
