<HEADLINE> Japan Must Take Correct Attitude To History: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's People's Daily Thursday
carries a signed article titled "A Correct Attitude Toward History
is the Political Basis for Sino-Japanese Friendship."
</P>
<P>
The full text of the article by Gu Ping is as follows:
</P>
<P>
A lot of thoughts are coming up in my mind on the occasion of
commemorating the 60th anniversary of the July 7 Incident, or the
Marco Polo Bridge Incident, in suburban Beijing in 1937.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan are close neighbors separated by only a strip
of water, and the two countries' friendly exchanges could be
traced back to more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
But earlier in this century, Japan took a militarist course of
aggression and expansion, therefore inflicted severe sufferings to
the people of China and some other Asian nations, as well as the
Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
As a Chinese saying goes: "Past experience, if not forgotten,
is a guide for the future." This painful part of history should be
forever in our memory.
</P>
<P>
A correct attitude toward the history of Japan's militarist
aggression always serves as the political basis for Sino-Japanese
relations.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government acknowledged in the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement of 1972 that "the Japanese side is keenly aware of
Japan's responsibility for causing enormous damage in the past to
the Chinese people through war and deeply reproaches itself."
</P>
<P>
It was with this basic understanding by the Japanese side about
its past that the Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations were
normalized at the time. In the 25 years thereafter, Japanese
leaders in general have shown a gradual progress toward a better
understanding on this point.
</P>
<P>
On August 15, 1995, then Japanese Prime Minister Tomiichi
Murayama made a statement on behalf of his government, deeply
reproaching and sincerely apologizing for the tremendous loss and
pains that Japan's colonial rules and aggressions caused to the
peoples of Asian nations. The move had a positive bearing on
pushing forward the smooth development of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, however, it is obvious that there has always been an
adverse current in Japan against the healthy growth of the
country's relations with China.
</P>
<P>
One major sign pointing to the existence of such a
countercurrent is Japanese right-wing forces' consistent advocacy
of the reactionary view of history trying to whitewash the
country's wars of aggression.
</P>
<P>
It's astonishing to find that in a Japanese publication
compiled to review the so-called Great East Asia War, a lengthy
part is devoted to promoting the reactionary view of history and
reversing the verdict of history.
</P>
<P>
In its discussions about Japan's aggression against China, the
same publication undisguisedly mispresents the Japanese-instigated
September 18 Incident of 1931 in China as a "war of defense" on
Japan's part, the July 7 Incident of 1937 as the result of a
"conspiracy" on China's part, and Japan's Twenty-one Demands
imposed on China's Northern Warlords government early in this
century as a Japanese effort to "consolidate Japan's vested
interest."
</P>
<P>
In one word, the publication seems to be trying to wipe out all
historic facts about the Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, Japan pursued a basic state policy of
expansionism after the Meiji Restoration. In the 1930s, by
instigating the September 18 Incident and the July 7 Incident,
Japan launched a full-scale war of aggression against China.
</P>
<P>
There is mass of irrefutable evidence for the countless crimes
and atrocities the Japanese army committed during the 1931-45 war
of aggression against China. And these crimes and atrocities
always get people's hackles up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Must Take Correct Attitude To History: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, some frantic militarist trumpeters in nowadays Japan
are trying to justify the crimes and atrocities by saying that
"for its lack of land and resources, sometimes Japan needs to ask
other countries for the rights and interests required for its own
survival." What a logic of bandits!
</P>
<P>
The absurd statement sounds so similar to what the Japanese
militarists said when they launched aggression wars many years
ago. It seems that these people are still living in the militarist
fanaticism in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
These same people have also been fiercely attacking the
Japanese politicians who uphold an objective view of history. They
are angry with people of integrity in the circles of education and
press in Japan. They whine that Japan is suffering from "national
self-maltreatment" and "historic self-maltreatment."
</P>
<P>
They turn blind eyes to all testimonies, material evidences and
hills of records in China, Japan and other places worldwide about
Japan's war crimes and atrocities.
</P>
<P>
They ignore the desire cherished by both the Japanese and
Chinese peoples to pass a friendship from generation to
generation, and fabricate arguments and quibbles to whitewash
Japan's wars of aggression.
</P>
<P>
They have even called for changing the status quo and
re-establish what they say is a "correct" view of history so as to
restore "national self-confidence" and "national spirit."
</P>
<P>
We must point out that Japanese militarists back many years ago
also advocated the so-called "national spirit" when they launched
aggression wars. It was this "national spirit" that caused severe
sufferings to Asian peoples, including the Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
Today, these people are picking up again the "national spirit."
Where on earth are they going to lead Japan to? What international
image are they going to help make for Japan?
</P>
<P>
Their words and deeds will only remind Japan's neighboring
countries to keep greater vigilance against Japan and hurt Japan's
own future development.
</P>
<P>
Sensible statesmen and people of insight in Japan should not
keep their eyes closed and let their country be led astray by
these people.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this century, Japan has tried on two
diametrically opposite development paths which brought it two
kinds of totally different outcomes. By comparing the two, it is
not difficult to conclude that Japan's fundamental interests lie
in sticking to the road of peaceful development.
</P>
<P>
What is good and bad is quite obvious and historic lessons are
still fresh. But some arrogant people in Japan have lost
themselves and attempted to revive the dream of a militarist
Japan. So it is necessary for us to warn them that they have to
respect history and learn from it, or they will be punished by it.
</P>
<P>
As an old Chinese saying goes, it takes courage to acknowledge
one's own shame. It means to Japan that it should have the courage
to face up to history and deeply repoach for its past mistakes,
and continue on the road of peaceful development to win the trust
of other Asian countries and become a decent member of the world
community.
</P>
<P>
History is a mirror and how to look into it reflects the state
of a nation's spirit and political attitude. In the history of
mankind, it is not rare that a nation misguides itself and falls
into a trap. What is important is that the nation should have the
courage and wisdom to get itself out from the trap. A correct view
of history often serves as a turning point for a nation to make
progress back on the road of development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people hope that Japan will choose the road of
peaceful development and carry the Sino-Japanese friendship from
generation to generation. And a start point of the road is to have
a correct attitude toward history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
