<HEADLINE> Joint Communique Results in Mixed Reactions in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Madrid joint communique issued
Tuesday by Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis sparked mixed reactions in Greece.
</P>
<P>
The six-point communique includes the mutual respect of each
other's sovereignty, of international law and treaties.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also pledged to solve their disputes
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government hailed the document.
</P>
<P>
Simitis described the joint communique as "a document of
principles which will govern Greek-Turkish ties."
</P>
<P>
Acting government spokesman Nikos Athanasakis said today that
the joint communique was "a particularly positive development"
which could open up "a new era" in Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
However, the Communist Party today expressed concern about the
document, saying that it was not aimed at resolving differences
between the two countries, but at extending "U.S. influence" in
the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Coalition of the Left and Progress said in a statement that
the joint communique could serve as "a step towards the
normalization of Greek-Turkish ties."
</P>
<P>
The coalition called for an immediate meeting of political
party leaders in order to be briefed in detail on the course of
Athens' ties with Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Social Movement sees the joint communique
"overturning the substance of the existing legal situation in the
Aegean" and being "a prelude to the partitioning and joint
sovereignty" of the sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
