<HEADLINE> Militiamen Sent to Improve N. Mogadishu's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- North Mogadishu authorities have
handed over 300 militiamen to the dormant Islamic court to
improve the worsening security situation in the northern part of
the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
During a ceremony at the former traffic police headquarters on
Tuesday, acting chairman of Ali Mahdi's faction Ali Ugas Abdulle
said the militiamen together with their technical wagons will be
at the disposal of the Islamic court chaired by religious leader
Sheikh Ali Sheikh Mohamud (Sheikh Ali Dhere).
</P>
<P>
Ali Ugas said all armored cars and armed militiamen are
prohibited from moving along the streets of North Mogadishu
except those serving the Islamic court with legal documents.
</P>
<P>
However, the effectiveness of the militiamen is yet to be seen
in the streets despite people's eagerness for peace.
</P>
<P>
Ali Ugas said this contingent will be reinforced by more
troops to restore and rule of law and order in North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
On the day when the court resumed its function yesterday, four
BAH352SPC131S09PCQL00:3200:321105
people were killed and several others wounded when a gunman
opened fire at random on a civilian bus in North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to a witness, the killer was one of the gunmen who
controlled an illegal check point extorting money from the
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The witness said the killer himself was shot dead on the spot
by a guard of the bus who returned fire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, faction leader of south Mogadishu Hussein Mohamed
Aidid today appointed a 14-member committee for the emergence
situation.
</P>
<P>
According to a decree which was broadcast on a radio which
backs Hussein Aidid, the 14 members will be headed by Aidid
himself and will be responsible for the restoration of peace in
Somalia. Hussoin Aidid is currently on a tour of Nairobi.
</P>
</TEXT>
