<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Reshuffle Passes Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- After several delays and tense
inner bickering within the coalition, the Israeli cabinet
reshuffle presented by Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu passed
the Knesset (Parliament) today.
</P>
<P>
In a vote of 52-46, the Knesset approved the new line-up of
cabinet, in which former Justice Minister Yaacov Neeman was
appointed the new finance minister and Likud's Knesset faction
HAB249HAB258i0709QU00:3200:320114
head Michael Eitan the new science minister.
</P>
<P>
Neeman, who does not belong to any political party, replaced
Dan Meridor who resigned last month due to his rift with
Netanyahu. Eitan replaced Benny Begin who resigned in January to
protest the signing of Israeli-Palestinian agreement on Israeli
troop redeployment in the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Likud lawmaker Silvan Shalom was appointed deputy
defense minister and he will take over the science portfolio from
Eitan after one year in rotation.
</P>
<P>
Not everyone within the coalition was pleased with the new
appointments, which have been achieved after so much inner
bickering and bargains conducted among the coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Education, Culture and Arts Zevulun Hammer of the
National Religious Party, Public Security Minister Avigdor
Kahalani of the Third Way Party, and Labor and Social Affairs
Minister Eli Ishai of Shas Party were absent from today's vote on
the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu expressed confidence after the vote, saying that the
new cabinet would be stronger and more stable, while
acknowledging it would still face more difficulties and challenges
ahead.
</P>
<P>
"I think the government was measurably strengthened today with
these excellent people, each in his own field," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he also believed that the new cabinet would help push
forward the peace process and achieve the goals of economic and
social revolutions, such as ensuring a secure peace and realizing
the liberalization of economy.
</P>
<P>
Neeman was appointed only after Netanyahu's failing in his
attempt to transfer the hardline National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon to the finance portfolio. Sharon conditioned the
transfer on his inclusion into the powerful inner cabinet, which
comprises of Netanyahu, Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
Fearing that Sharon could jeopardize the peace process if
granted greater say in the decision-making process, both Levy and
Mordechai opposed Sharon's inclusion into the inner
cabinet. Netanyahu later dropped Sharon and decided to abolish the
inner cabinet, or kitchen cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Asked what role would Sharon play in future peace process,
Netanyahu said he valued Sharon's advices and would consult with
him on important decisions. There are already worries that Sharon
might take revenge in future on Netanyahu for dumping him in the
reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Eitan's entry into the cabinet was a welcome sign for the
well-wishers for the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace
process. Eitan, a dove in the rightist Likud, was known for
drawing a joint document with Labor lawmaker Yossi Beilin on the
final Israeli-Palestinian settlement that would grant high
autonomy to the Palestinians.
S05063HAB258I0709QU00:3200:330120
</P>
<P>
Eitan said after the Knesset vote that he would do his best to
help establish a national unity government in order to achieve
the final settlement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that Israeli people and Israeli nation will be
better represented and will be able to achieve better achievement
in the negotiations if there is a unity government," Eitan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
