<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Former Political Detainee Allowed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
relaxed its restriction order on Chia Thye Poh, a former political
detainee who had been detained by the government from 1966 to
1989, and granted him an international passport, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that this meant Chia could now travel out of
Singapore without a previously required written permission from
the Internal Security Department (ISD) under the Home Affairs
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said that Chia, 56, has been offered a one
year scholarship to study in Germany and he plans to leave at the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
With restriction relaxed, he would no longer need permission
from the ISD to take up a new job or change his address. But other
rules under the Restriction Order still apply and he still needs
approval from the ISD Director to speak in public.
</P>
<P>
He is also not allowed to associate with other former political
detainees. Chia was arrested under the Internal Security Act more
than 30 years ago for his alleged links with the Communist Party
of Malaya, which he had been denying, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, he was released and allowed to live and work in the
Sentosa Island. Later he was allowed to live with his parents in
their home on the main island of Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
