<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Official Denies Peso Devaluation Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Trade and Industry
Secretary Cesar Bautista today denied a report by Singapore Strait
Times that a peso devaluation agenda is in the offing in today's
meeting of the Monetary Board.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, Bautista stated that he personally does
not favor devaluation because a market-led mechanism is definitely
a more realistic mechanism to determine value of the currency.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the Monetary Board, a body under the Central
Bank, merely focuses on the caucus on global competitiveness held
on July 4 wherein foreign exchange rate was one of the concerns
identified by businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Bautista explained that the foreign exchange policy
is an area under the sole jurisdiction of the Monetary Board, an
independent body.
</P>
<P>
He stated that he will merely transmit the paper of the
businessmen to the governor of the Monetary Board for information.
</P>
<P>
The governor usually dialogues with representatives of the
private sector to explain and give a clearer picture of the
specific policies which may be of concern to them.
</P>
<P>
Also today, President Fidel Ramos criticized the Singaporean
paper for "a media disinformation campaign of some kind" to
undermine the peso.
</P>
<P>
"It was observed that this is the second time in a row that
newspaper twisted statements of high-ranking Philippine officials
on the same subject, the first of which was Finance Secretary
Bobby de Ocampo," Ramos told his weekly press conference.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Strait Times quoted De Ocampo as saying the peso
may drop in a couple of weeks. The report, which was also
vehemently denied by De Ocampo, triggered a fresh wave of
speculative attacks on the peso Monday and forced the Philippine
Central Bank to raise its borrowing rates sharply.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said there could be a deliberate attempt by "outside
forces" to undermine the value of the peso as indicated by the
recent chain of events that led to the jittering of the country's
currency.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out the devaluation of the peso, saying that the
macroeconomic parameters, policies and condition of the country
remain "sound".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
