<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health of Russian School Children Deteriorating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia's school children are in
worse shapes in the 1990s as only 10 percent of them now appear to
be in good physical conditions, a Russian official said today.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of primary and secondary school students have
chronic diseases, said Yekaterina Lakhova, who presides over a
presidential committee on women, family and population affairs.
</P>
<P>
Findings from a latest survey also suggest that the rest of the
country's school children may have other health problems, Lakhova
was quoted as saying by an Interfax news agency report.
</P>
<P>
Students aged between 15 to 17 are in the worst shape, as their
incidences of blood diseases and endocrine diseases have shot up
by 260 percent and 220 percent respectively since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The official also expressed worries that the incidences of
contagious diseases are increasing in schools.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, she said, the number of school children
suffering from tuberculosis was up 1.7 times, and the cases of
adolescents who contracted syphilis soared 49 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
