<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's GDP Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
of Nepal in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending on July 14 is lower
compared with the last fiscal year, a latest survey said.
</P>
<P>
This is mainly due to the decline in the growth rate of
agricultural and non-agricultural sectors, the Economic Survey for
Fiscal Year 1996-97 said.
</P>
<P>
Among the nine sectors contributing to the growth of GDP, all
the major sectors except manufacturing, electricity, gas and water
experienced slower growth this year, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey said the GDP of the current fiscal year grew only
4.9 percent as against 6.1 percent for the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
This rate is lower than the average growth rate of South Asian
countries, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, as a result of liberal and open economic policy
adopted by the government in recent years, the industrial sector
has seen increase both in domestic and foreign investment in the
passing fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The survey said a total of 356 joint ventures have been
approved by April 1997, with a foreign investment of some 10
billion rupees (about 180 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
