<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Should Pay More for Entering NATO: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen today asked Hungary to spend more on defense for
entering the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Hungary's defense budget, now 1.2 percent of its gross domestic
product (GDP), should rise to 2.1 or 2.2 percent, Cohen told a
press conference on the second day of his three-day stay here.
</P>
<P>
In the coming 13 years, 27 to 35 billion U.S. dollars is needed
for the NATO expansion to include East European nations, with
Hungary as one of the first new members, the U.S. defense chief
said.
</P>
<P>
The cost incurred, he said, should be split into three equal
parts and shared by the United States, the 16-nation Western
military alliance's other members and the would-be new members.
</P>
<P>
He promised, at the presence of his Hungarian counterpart
Keleti Gyorgy, that the United States would help with the
personnel and language training of the Hungarian military.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Keleti said the Hungarian military could gear up
to the NATO standard in eight or 10 years, and the priority is to
consolidate the air force's combat and defense capabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
