<HEADLINE> SFOR Confirms Catching War Crime Indictees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Nato-led Stablization Force
(SFOR) on Thursday confirmed that it had launched its first
operation to catch war crime indictees since deployment, killing
one and arresting alive another.
</P>
<P>
The operation was carried out by the British troops in
Prijedor, the northwestern Bosnian town in the Serb-controlled
territory.
</P>
<P>
Simo Drljaca, former police chief in Prijedor, was killed in
the operation when he opened fire on SFOR soldiers as they
approached for the purpose of detaining him, said a SFOR
statement.
</P>
<P>
One British soldier was wounded in the shooting with Drljaca.
</P>
<P>
Another suspect, Milan Kovacevic, was arrested without incident
at a hospital where he was working at director.
</P>
<P>
SFOR spokesman Major Chris Riley said that Kovacevic would be
handed over to the international Criminal Tribunal for Former
Yugoslavia which has charged the Serb and dozens of his fellow
nationals for war crimes in the three-and-half year Bosnian war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
