<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Small Enterprises Face Challenges, Chances: TDC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized
enterprises, which form the backbone of Hong Kong's economy, face
a new era of both unprecedented competitive challenges and strong
opportunities for growth, a trade official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC), stressed the need for local small and medium-sized
enterprises to equip themselves to face the tough competition
ahead and to step up efforts to penetrate into new market fronts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar marking the opening of the TDC's annual
Market Day Exhibition at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center Extension, he pointed out: "Changing times have created new
competitive challenges for local small and medium-sized
enterprises."
</P>
<P>
Many small and medium-sized enterprises have not yet made the
adjustment to operating in a high cost economy, and they have not
identified past inefficiencies or incorporated cost saving
information and managerial systems, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, these enterprises have successfully
diversified their production processes by expanding out of Hong
Kong. But with ever-changing consumer trends, and demands from the
marketplace for faster product deliver, they face a big
challenge, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Fung said that the small and medium-sized enterprises
are also "in a good position as a new era of opportunity opens,"
referring to Hong Kong's return to China and the establishment of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is now in the best economic shape to advance herself
as a Special Administrative Region, moving towards a more
affluent and market-oriented regional economy and is set to
penetrate into bigger overseas markets," the TDC chairman noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
