<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault Belgian Workers to Vote on Layoff Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian employees of the
French automaker Renault will vote directly on its layoff plan on
July 17, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
There seemed no other alternative left after company
negotiators and trade unions failed Wednesday to reach an
agreement on the planned closure of the Vilvoorde plant in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
During an all-night meeting with union representatives that
ended Wednesday morning, Renault said that it would preserve 600
jobs and offered severance pay packages ranging from 150,000 to
two million Belgian francs (4,130 to 55,140 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The offer will be reportedly more than the workers would get if
the plant was declared bankrupt. The management of the plant was
threatening to close the factory if the workers did not agree,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached a framework accord last Thursday, but
details remain to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
"We are dealing with unacceptable blackmail by management,
which has threatened to place the plant in receivership if its
proposal is not accepted," a trade union spokesman was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Renault, which initially wanted to save only 400 jobs at the
Belgian plant, offered to help save 600 at the meeting with the
Belgian unions.
</P>
<P>
Renault is planning to close the plant before the end of this
year but to continue to use the site for subcontracting work and
for maintenance work on used cars.
</P>
<P>
The company, over the objection of the Belgian government,
decided to close the plant and shift production to Spain and
France to save money.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimate that the closure would save at least 800
million French francs (some 135 million dollars) a year and help
the company break even this year.
</P>
<P>
If workers reject Renault's offer and the company decides to
let its Belgian unit be declared bankrupt, employees will be
entitled to about one-third as much compensation as the company is
currently offering.
</P>
<P>
Shares of Renault rose 2.40 French francs to close at 146.10 as
investors in Paris favored shares of companies involved in
restructuring operations.
</P>
<P>
Renault also plans to cut about 3,000 jobs in France this year
out of a worldwide work force of 141,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
