<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Raises Interest Rates to Curb Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain raised official interest
rates to 6.75 percent from 6.50 percent today in a bid to curb
consumer spending and cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
This is the second rate rise since the Bank of England was
given the power to set interest rates two months ago.
</P>
<P>
The move followed data showing the inflation rate overshot the
government's 2.5 percent target in June to stand at 2.7 percent.
The first budget announced last week by the new Labor government
was seen as being not sufficiently tough to rein in consumer
demand.
</P>
<P>
The Bank said the strength of the pound, up over 20 percent
against major currencies since last August, complicated the rate
decision but the recent run of strong economic data in the end
forced its hand.
</P>
<P>
"The upward revision of estimated output growth in the fourth
quarter of 1996 and recent development in monetary growth and
retail sales indicated that a further tightening of monetary
policy was necessary," the Bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The government immediately backed the rate rise. In a statement
released after the Bank's announcement, Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown said it was important that inflation be
brought under control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
