<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Announces Aid Suspension to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The German government today announced
that it was suspending all further development aid to Cambodia
after the latest developments in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
"Development cooperation with Cambodia will be suspended,
effective immediately," Germany's Development Aid Minister
Carl-Dieter Spranger said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that Bonn was consulting with other European Union
member states on possible further steps against Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Germany resumed aid to Cambodia in 1992, and has so far donated
or pledged a total of 119 million marks (68 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move by the German government was greeted today by
Cambodia's opposition leader Sam Rainsy, who is here on a visit.
</P>
<P>
According to Rainsy, a former finance minister, foreign aid
accounted for about 60 percent of Cambodia's state expenditures.
</P>
</TEXT>
