<HEADLINE> First Jordanian Plane in 7 Years Lands in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The first Jordanian aircraft
landed at Kuwaiti International Airport this morning and then
returned back to Jordan after a seven-year break of direct flights
between the two countries since the Gulf crisis in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti airport officials said that the 102-seat Royal
Jordanian company Airbus A-320 touched down at 11:45 local
time (08:45 GMT) with 40 passengers on board and left fully
packed an hour later.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Kuwait resumed direct air flights Wednesday, with
the first Kuwaiti commercial plane of Kuwait Airways Corporation
(KAC) landing at Amman's Queen Alia International Airport, the
first flight since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait froze its links with Jordan, including direct flights by
the flag carriers, after accusing Amman of siding with Iraq
during Iraqi occupation of Kuwait between August 1990 and February
1991.
</P>
<P>
Last month, KAC and Royal Jordanian company struck an accord to
resume two-way semi-weekly direct flights within the framework of
relations normalization process started last year between the two
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, KAC started its semi-weekly flights to Amman, on
every Wednesday and Friday, while the Royal Jordanian company from
today resumes the semi-weekly flights, on every Monday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has not restored its full diplomatic relations with
Jordan, with only a Charge D'Affaires in Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Decades-Old Coffee Program Fails: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The coffee development
program in Ethiopia over the past 40 years has failed to boost
productivity and quality, the Ethiopian News Agency today quoted
a research paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper was presented at a workshop here under the theme
Strategy and the Execution of the Extension Program of the Coffee
and Tea Industry. It said despite the possibility to produce 20
quintals of coffee per hectare, only four or five quintals is
produced.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the coffee program's unsatisfactory
result is due to the failure to take into consideration the
social and cultural values of the farmers, as well as the
participation of the consumers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the paper said, quantity, technology, sales and
supply of coffee were pre-determined by higher authorities
instead of the farmers themselves.
</P>
<P>
The study recommended that the coffee development extension
program expected to be implemented in the future must take into
account the natural environment, social and cultural values,
problems and interests of the farmers, as well as the
participation of the producers.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is a major coffee producer and exporter in Africa. It
earned close to 300 million U.S. Dollars from export of 128,000
tons of coffee in the just ended 1996/97 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
