<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Budget of Nepal Focuses on Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Finance Minister Rabindra
Nath Sharma said here today that higher and sustainable economic
growth, poverty alleviation and rural development will be the
government's top priorities in the coming fiscal year beginning on
July 15.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the budget draft for the fiscal year 1997-98 at the
joint session of the bicameral parliament, Sharma said the budget
focuses primarily on projects that will directly contribute to the
upliftment of the poor, control public consumption expenditure,
and create a conducive atmosphere to encourage the private sector
to mobilize its skills and resources for the economic development
of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will give emphasis on agricultural
development by providing impetus to rural development, the
Agricultural Perspective Plan will be implemented with the
emphasis on commercialization of agricultural sector in order to
support the acceleration of the overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the liberal, open and market oriented economic
policy will be gradually broadened and strengthened for
sustainable higher growth rate in non-agricultural sector, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that 45 percent of the people of the country live below
poverty line, Sharma stressed that sectoral and targeted programs
will be executed in a more coordinated, integrated and effective
manner so as to reduce poverty on a long term basis.
</P>
<P>
To this end, a high level Poverty Alleviation Commission will
be set up in the coming fiscal year to conduct poverty alleviation
campaign with the streamlining of development strategies, programs
and targets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Agricultural Perspective Plan, a package program of
fertilizer, irrigation, technology, road, electricity and market
will be carried out, he said, adding by successfully implementing
the plan, it is expected that the population living below poverty
line will be brought down to 12.5 percent by the end of the Ninth
Five Year Plan period (1997-2002).
</P>
<P>
The government has also taken human resource development as an
integral part of poverty alleviation and decided to invest
substantially in programs like basic and primary health, education
and rural safe drinking water, Sharma said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
