<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Proposes to Tackle Delayed Commercial Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- All efforts should be made to
establish a climate in Europe where payments in commercial
transactions are made on time, an EU (European Union) official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Christos Papoutsis, EU commissioner for enterprise policy, said
Thursday that such problems should be tackled as a matter of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
"Minimum requirements should be incorporated into national
legislation, for example, concerning the statutory right of
creditors to interest on late payments," he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, Thursday
adopted a communication on late payments in commercial
transactions on the initiative of Papoutsis.
</P>
<P>
The EC notes that increasingly long payment periods can have
serious consequences for all European firms, particularly small
and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), by undermining their cash
flows, profitability and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The competitive position of SMEs as suppliers to large firms
can be distorted by deliberately long payment delays, the EC
maintains.
</P>
<P>
The payments situation is also hindering the development of
intra-EU trade and the smooth functioning of the internal market,
according to the communication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
