<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Japanese Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng told a
group of Japanese businessmen here today that the competition in
the China market is fierce, and only those with advanced
technology and reasonable prices can get the upper hand in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a meeting with Hiroshi Watanabe, chairman of
the Sanwa Bank Ltd of Japan, and his party here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li briefed the visitors on China's economic situation and the
prospects for the country's central and western areas. Many
Japanese enterprises are actively exploring the possibilities of
cooperating with China's inland provinces and municipalities, Li
said, adding that this is far-sighted.
</P>
<P>
He adviced the entrepreneurs from Japan to decide their
cooperation projects according to the different advantages and
priorities of those provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
China is a developing country, but its development is rapid and
there are rapidly changes in the structure of its industries, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes overseas businessmen to cooperate in
skill-intensive industries, Li said. He hoped that Japanese
enterprises would notice these changes in the China market and
provide advanced technologies in collaboration with their Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Li went on to say that the Sanwa Bank is one of the biggest
corporations in Japan, and its business has extended to many
Chinese areas and enterprises. He said he hoped that Sanwa and its
subsidiaries would play an active role in securing healthy and
stable Sino-Japanese ties and in promoting mutually-beneficial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Watanabe told Li that the mission of his delegation in China is
to become better acquainted with the new developments in China's
economy so as to expand Japan's economic and technological
cooperation with China. The Sanwa Bank will implement well its
current joint projects with China and gradually strengthen its
cooperation with China's inland provinces, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
