<HEADLINE> Manila Extends Truce in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military today
extended its unilateral truce in Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, for four more days until next Tuesday to give a
chance for the resumption of peace talks with Muslim rebels.
</P>
<P>
Acedera, the Armed Force's chief of staff, said the extension
of the ceasefire was aimed at giving Autonomous Region of Muslim
Mindanao Governor Nur Misuari enough time to persuade the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The original ceasefire, ordered by President Fidel Ramos, will
expire at 6 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
Misuari was earlier asked by Ramos to mediate between the
government and the MILF. The MILF suspended the peace talks late
last month after its second biggest camp in Cotabato province was
seized by the military.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Acedera dismissed the MILF's accusations that the
military is organizing a paramilitary force, the Christian
Liberation Movement, to fight the MILF. Acedera said the military
is too busy to do this.
</P>
<P>
Also today, MILF Vice Chairman Murad said the MILF laid down
four conditions for reopening the peace talks during its first
meeting Wednesday with Misuari in its biggest headquarters, Camp
Abubakar, in Maguindanao province, western Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The four conditions include the pull-out of military troops in
"MILF-controlled areas", the cessation of military operations
against the MILF and the return of evacuees to their original
places.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been raging between the MILF and government troops
during the past several weeks in central and western Mindanao,
killing over 150 people and displacing more than 70,000 residents.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
