<HEADLINE> Chinese Sets Sixth World Record as India Tastes Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGZHOU, Southeast China, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Chen
Xiaomin rewrote a world record as India won its first gold medal
at the Asian weightlifting championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chen lifted 107.5 kilograms to break the snatch world mark en
route to winning all three titles for the women's 64kg category.
The previous record of 106 kilograms was set by Chinese Li Hongyun
in May last year.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth world record produced in the first three days
of the championships.
</P>
<P>
After the record-breaking effort, the 20-year-old Chen lifted
127.5 kilograms in clean and jerk to total 235 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jen-Lien of Chinese Taipei took all three silver medals
and 18-year-old Chinese Hou Kangfeng finished third in three
events.
</P>
<P>
Malleswari won the first gold medal for India as she totalled
217.5 kilograms to come first at the 59kg division.
</P>
<P>
Wu Mei-Yi of Chinese Taipei, who got the snatch title with a
lift 97.5 kilograms, faded in the clean and jerk event to finish
third overall.
</P>
<P>
Patmawati of Indonesia took the clean and jerk title with a
lift of 120 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Chinese didn't compete in the 59kg class. 
</P>
</TEXT>
