<HEADLINE> Dhaka Appoints New Chairman of Securities, Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
chosen Abu Sayeed as the new chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC), the watch-dog of this country's
turbulent capital market, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayeed, a retired civil servant and chairman of Rupali Bank
Ltd, would be the third chairman of the SEC since its inception in
1993 and would replace Haroon Rashid who earlier resigned in June.
</P>
<P>
Haroon, who took office last August, could not complete his
three-year tenure due to his poor managing in handling the share
scam that rocked the capital market during the second half of
1996, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In this country's biggest-ever stock scandal, dozens of
security companies and leading brokers allegedly manipulated the
stock market, which witnessed a sharp up and down in a few months.
</P>
<P>
The SEC has been under big pressure for its poor managing and
slow-reaction to the stock scam, which made thousands of small
investors lost their wealth overnight.  
</P>
</TEXT>
