<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- The death toll from a massive flash flood and
landslide triggered by torrential rains in Kagoshima Prefecture,
southwestern Japan, early Thursday, has risen to 19 with two
people still missing and 13 injured, police said.
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- The Canadian government Thursday expressed its
concern over violence in Cambodia and called for a peaceful
resolution of the disputes between the co-prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is very concerned about the situation in Cambodia,"
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- The Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) decided Thursday to delay the entry of Cambodia
indefinitely, said Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a special meeting of ASEAN foreign
ministers here which "reviewed the situation in Cambodia in all
aspects," he told a crowded news conference after the six-hour
meeting.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The U.N. Special Envoy on Afghanistan, Nobert
Holl, left here Thursday for the northern Afghan town of
Mazar-e-Sharif to try to bring the warring Afghan groups to
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Holl's visit to Mazar-e-Sharif is part of the continued
diplomatic efforts by the UN to achieve durable peace in the
war-torn central Asian country.
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- At least 19,200 Ugandans have fled their homes in
the west to seek shelters in eastern Congo. They left their home
in Bundibugyo District to escape harassment from the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) rebels. 
