<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Raises Anew Borrowing Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank today
hiked its overnight borrowing rate to a four-year high of 32
percent from 30 percent in a bid to ward off speculative attacks
on the country's currency peso.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth time for the central bank to raise its key
interest rate to counter speculations against the peso since the
start of this month.
</P>
<P>
The country's currency has been under speculative attacks since
the start of July amid the rumors that the Philippine government
may devalue the peso after the floatation of the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
Speculations intensified in the foreign exchange market this
week after a Singapore-based newspaper quoted two high-ranking
financial officials as saying the Philippine is considering to
depreciate the peso. The reports were all bluntly denied.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the central bank was forced to raise the overnight
borrowing rate to 30 percent from 24 percent Monday. The overnight
borrowing rate stood at 15 percent on July 2.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the central bank was forced to dip into its
foreign reserves to meet a rising demand for dollars in the
currency market.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate remained stable at 26.40 pesos to one dollar
in today's currency market.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the central bank said raising the interest rate is
the best way to protect the peso since higher interest rate will
increase the cost of speculations.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here said continued high interest rate will affect
corporations and the property sector and then hurt the local stock
market which has already been tumbling since Monday.
</P>
<P>
The stock market today also plunged 78.05 points to close at
2,511.15, the lowest in two years, due to the new round of raise
in the borrowing rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
