<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's New Vehicle Sales Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's new motor vehicle sales
went up 1.8 percent in May, pushed by the strongest truck sales
ever, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 114,916 motor vehicles were sold in May, up from
112,849 sold in April but still below the 118,582 set in March.
</P>
<P>
New motor vehicle sales in Canada have been generally on the
upswing since April 1996, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The increase in truck sales resulted in a 2.3 percent gain over
April and a 20.5 percent jump compared with the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Sales of new trucks reached a monthly record of 53,083 in May.
</P>
<P>
Trucks include minivans, sport utility vehicles, light and heavy
trucks, vans, coaches and buses.
</P>
<P>
In May, Canadian consumers also purchased 61,833 new passenger
cars, 1.4 percent more than in April. The Big Three automakers
accounted for 59.8 percent of sales, while the other manufacturers
captured 40.2 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
Early indications of June sales suggest that there will be a
drop in total new motor vehicle sales, the agency added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
