<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Former Justice Minister Denies Sauna Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian former justice minister
Valentin Kovalyov has denied his relation to the published
scandalous photographs which caused him to resign, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kovalyov said, however, he wants to find out who gave
journalist Larisa Kislinskaya information compromising his
reputation, but has no intention to sue her.
</P>
<P>
In a live broadcast on Radio Echo of Moscow, the former justice
minister said, "My personal life remains unchanged as everything
on those scandalous photos definitely had no relation to me. I
firmly reject the authenticity of the tape scenes and facts of my
private life."
</P>
<P>
But he was reminded of the fact that Vice-Premier and Interior
Minister Anatoly Kulikov had said that the videotape showing the
then justice minister in a sauna with naked women was authentic.
</P>
<P>
In response, he said, "the truth will be restored. The video is
not authentic, it is unverified, and looks like it is forged."
</P>
<P>
"I want to restore my good name and my reputation by all legal
means," Kovalyov said, but refused "for tactical consideration" to
disclose what steps he intended to take.
</P>
<P>
Referring to suing the journalist, he said that she had yet to
realize the role she acted in someone's play. "I have no hostile
feelings about her. If this scandalous story can help her
journalistic career, good luck," Kovalyov said.
</P>
<P>
The former minister alleged that the scandal was organized by
the forces dissatisfied with the reform of the judicial bodies
initiated by him.
</P>
<P>
Kovalyov said that he believed the source of information would
be eventually punished.
</P>
<P>
Following the scandal, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
appointed Sergei Stepashin on July 2 as new justice minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
