<HEADLINE> S. Korean Retail Firms Rush to Foreign Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean major retail companies,
in bids to leave behind the ever harsh competition at home, are
now seeking to explore foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Haitai Store plans to set up a massive supermarket in the
United States around the end of this year while Hanhwa Store
intends to establish discount stores in China, Southeast Asia and
south Europe from next year.
</P>
<P>
The advancement into foreign markets by the firms began when
E-Mart of Shinsegae Department Store opened a sales outlet in
Shanghai, China, in February of this year.
</P>
<P>
LG Group is considering beginning operation in Southeast Asia
from next year in the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Association of Supermarkets decided to set up a
store complex in Danang, Vietnam, to market products manufactured
by South Korea's small and medium-sized firms.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Chain Stores also plans to open a pavilion
for South Korean products in Japan in April next year with a view
to expanding sales of domestic goods.
</P>
<P>
Sources foresee that an increasing number of marketing
companies are expected to rush to foreign markets once the
domestic market is saturated amid accelerating competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
