<HEADLINE> Canada Concerned Over Violence in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
expressed its concern over violence in Cambodia and called for a
peaceful resolution of the disputes between the co-prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is very concerned about the situation in Cambodia,"
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Reports of political killings are extremely disturbing. We
deeply regret that many people have lost their lives, including
one Canadian," he said.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy called for a peaceful resolution of the disputes
between First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
"Canada expects Cambodia's leaders to abide by the terms of the
Paris Accords and to resolve their differences through peaceful
political means."
</P>
<P>
"We urge that free and fair elections be held as scheduled in
1998," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed thanks to the Australian Embassy in Phnom
Penh for its assistance to Canadian citizens.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to the rival premiers were engaged in heavy
fighting in Phnom Penh and its vicinity on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Later, Hun Sen announced that the capital was under his control
and Ranariddh had been ousted.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh accused Hun Sen of staging a coup d'etat but Hun Sen
denied the charge.  
</P>
