<HEADLINE> Manila Maps up Plan to Boost Electronics Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
private sector are mapping up a master plan for the electronics
and semiconductor industry aimed at sustaining a 30 percent export
growth annually.
</P>
<P>
Cesar Mendigo, director of the Board of Investments, said the
master plan intends to further enhance the sector, particularly on
improving its value-add from 20-25 percent to over 40 percent by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Mendigo said in a statement that the government has tapped two
well-known international management consultant firms to work on
the design.
</P>
<P>
The consultants have initially identified areas which are
likely to bring more benefits to investors and existing players,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The firms will recommend measures for the sector to grow in the
next five years to 10 years, through which a more-focused
incentives for these products will be designed.
</P>
<P>
One of the solutions the sector is looking at, he said, is the
creation of domestic technology, which would allow the industry to
be more productive given a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
Mendigo said the government is keen on seeing the development
of world-class Philippine brand through the creation of computer
national brand product.
</P>
<P>
The master plan also outlines concerned sectors views on the
future trends in the industry, requirements as a scientific
investor in the Philippines and current and planned industry
development program in the country.
</P>
<P>
The electronics sector has posted impressive growth in terms of
investments, export earnings and employment despite the
difficulties besetting the country's economy in the past years.
</P>
<P>
The industry remained the country's top dollar earner for the
first half of 1997 with exports amounting to 4.4 billion US
dollars, up by 41 percent from a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
