<HEADLINE> Philippine Foreign Currency Deposits Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The foreign currency deposits in
the Philippine commercial banking system have reached a record
high of 16.8 billion US dollars during the first half of the year,
the Philippine Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a news release that this figure represented a
1 billion US dollars or a 6.35 percent jump from the end-May level
of 15.8 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The June 1997 level also registered a 5.1 billion US dollar
increase from a year-ago level of 11.7 billion dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
Although not officially counted as part of the country's gross
international reserves, it said, the deposits are considered as a
second layer of Philippine international reserves.
</P>
<P>
This is because that most of these accounts are held by local
exporters, companies with foreign exchange receipts, and families
of overseas Filipinos, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
