<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to See Trade Surplus of Over 100 Billion Marks, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany could expect a trade surplus
of more than 100 billion marks (57 billion U.S. dollar) in 1997,
with exports growing by six to seven percent and imports up four
to five percent, a leading industry group said today.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of German mark against U.S. dollar, the
massive rationalization in the German industry and the limited
increases in labour costs are factors which are helping to bolster
Germany's exports, said the German Council of Trade and Industry
(DIHT), the umbrella organization of chambers of commerce.
</P>
<P>
But it also warned against overstating the export success,
saying that Germany would see further losses in its share on the
world market because the world trade as a whole is expecting an
even stronger growth of over eight percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the expected German export growth in 1997 still
lagged behind the long-term average, which was more than 7.5
percent in the 1980s, the DIHT said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
