<HEADLINE> Manila to Relocate Squatters to Improve Flood Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government today
decided to relocate thousands of squatters living in waterways in
Metro Manila as a major solution to improve flood control
capability.
</P>
<P>
At a government meeting on flood control, the Housing and Urban
Development Coordinating Council and the National Housing
Authority were committed to providing some 27,000 sites for Metro
Manila squatters.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Public Works and Highways has identified
around 23,000 squatter families living near waterways all over the
capital region.
</P>
<P>
Public Works Secretary Gregorio Vigilar said one of the major
problems identified for flooding in Metro Manila was the blocked
drainage system.
</P>
<P>
The clogging was attributed to garbage thrown by the squatters
living along the region's main waterways.
</P>
<P>
The government was committed to undertaking the relocation
within a one-year period.
</P>
<P>
In May, several days of torrential rains caused heavy flooding
in Metro Manila, killing at least 11 people in the capital area.
This deadly flooding prompted President Fidel Ramos to call the
flood meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
