<HEADLINE> Australian Government to Sell Transmission Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 550 radio and television
transmitters around Australia were put up for sale today.
</P>
<P>
Federal Communications Minister Richard Alston announced the
sale of the National Transmission Agency's network by open tender.
</P>
<P>
Alston said in a statement that the buyer would be required to
accept five-year transmission contracts with the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) and the Special Broadcasting
Service, two national broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a requirement of the sale contract that national
coverage and existing service commitments to regional and rural
Australia be continued," he said.
</P>
<P>
The federal government would also ensure current social policy
obligations, including remote commercial television
re-transmission and emergency services, would be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Government sources refused to speculate on the likely sale
price, saying the value of the network would depend on the
opportunities seen by commercial operators.
</P>
<P>
However, one industry analyst said the federal government
could reap 225-300 million US dollars from the sale.  
</P>
