<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 19 in Japan Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from a massive flash
flood and landslide triggered by torrential rains in Kagoshima
Prefecture, southwestern Japan, early today, has risen to 19 with
two people still missing and 13 injured, police said.
</P>
<P>
Two of the injured remain in critical condition, Kyodo News
Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred along the Harihara River in the city of
Izumi at around 00:50 a.m., overflowing a landslide-protection
barrier and burying 15 homes with 39 residents under mud and rocks.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic heavy rains, coupled with tons of tree-covered mud,
rocks measuring more than five meters in diameter, hampered rescue
operations by some 860 fire fighters, police officers and members
of the Self-Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Agency issued a waring of heavy rain and
flooding Wednesday night in northern parts of Kagoshima Prefecture
that include Izumi. Since Monday, the city has recorded 483
millimeters of rain as of 11:00 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The site of the landslide is home to some 80 families, and 50
residents took shelter at local public facilities.
</P>
<P>
This is the worst landslide to hit Kagoshima since September of
1993 when 20 people were killed in the town of Kimpo in a
landslide unleashed by a typhoon.
</P>
<P>
Muneyuki Mutgami, a local official, was quoted as saying that
the landslide was the biggest he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
"I have engaged in work on disaster prevention for 30 years,
but I have not seen a landslide bigger than this." he said. "It's
an avalanche of a mountain hitting the village rather than a
landslide,"
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains also caused a landslide in the city of
Minamata in Kumamoto Prefecture next to Kagoshima Prefecture at
around 10:00 p.m., burying nine people under earth, all of whom were
rescued, police said.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Agency issued a warning of continued
torrential rains over an area ranging from the southeastern main
island of Kyushu to northern parts of the Kanto region
encompassing Tokyo and its neighboring prefectures up to Friday
morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
