<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Health Minister Advocates Sex Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's top health official today
admitted a lack of sex knowledge among children and young people
and advocated sex education through parents but not at schools.
</P>
<P>
Addressing some 300 professionals and health experts on the
occasion of the World Population Day, Health Minister Alireza
Marandi said "many of the divorces, about half of them, take
place because of lack of familiarity with sexual issues."
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicated an increase of 8.86 percent in
divorce rate in the last Iranian calendar year (March 22, 1996-
March 21, 1997) compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In this period a total of 479,263 pairs got married while
37,817 cases of divorce were finalized in Iranian court, the
figures showed.
</P>
<P>
Marandi stated that his ministry had set up some 450
pre-wedding counseling centers to inform the would-be couples of
sexual issues.
</P>
<P>
However, he said "Parents are the best sources to teach sexual
issues to their children." The parents can get their training from
a Parent-Teacher Association.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the ceremony today, Marandi told Xinhua
that he is opposed to sex education in the Iranian schools
because, as he put it, "our society is not ready for it."
</P>
<P>
But he criticized the present state in Iran's traditional
society in which parents are reluctant to talk to their children
about sex.
</P>
<P>
"Teaching children about sex is absolutely important for the
good of the family and the nation. Teaching about sex is a way to
reduce population growth," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran's population growth has been phenomenal since the Islamic
revolution in 1979. The population doubled since then. The latest
census conducted in October 1996 showed Iran's population stood at
60,055,000 and the Interior Ministry even put it at 62 million at
present.
</P>
<P>
The government now encourages family planning in order to
check population growth. Condoms and contraceptive are sold
over-the-counter at pharmacies; state food subsidies only go
to the first three children of a family.
</P>
<P>
Posters around the capital of Tehran went even further by
saying "One is good, two is enough."
</P>
<P>
However, abortion is not an option in the Islamic country.
Illegitimate and surreptitious operations are offered at
exorbitant rates by physicians or even midwives, which might prove
fatal.
</P>
<P>
Iranian media often report arrests of individuals, mostly
women, for performing abortions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Minorities to Use Own Languages in School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government passed
an urgent order on July 9 to amend the educational law so as to
allow minority nationalities to use their own languages in schools.
</P>
<P>
The existing law, passed in 1995, says that the Romanian
language is the only language to be used in school teaching.
</P>
<P>
However, it has met opposition from the minority party -- The
Hungarian Democratic Union of Romania, which has requested
amendments to the law to meet the demands of the minorities since
it became a ruling party in the November 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
Under the amended law, high and elementary schools of
minorities in Romania will use their national languages in
teaching, but the Romanian language will still remain a major
course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
