<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TBL Sets Good Example of Divestiture in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Breweries Limited
(TBL) stands out as one of the most successful cases since the
government embarked on the program of divestiture of parastatal
organisations some four years ago, the Daily News repoted today.
</P>
<P>
TBL is a joint venture between the Tanzanian government and Indol, a
subsidiary of the world renowned beer producer, the South African
Breweries (SAB). Tanzania owns 40.5 percent shares in TBL, while
Indol has 45 percent, the rest are owned by a few financial investors.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the performance of TBL has significantly improved
-- production has trippled and its contribution to government's
revenue increased.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the TBL Board Chairman, Paul Bomani, as
saying that TBL was now dominating the domestic market, unlike
what was the case years ago, when shelves in shops and bars
prominently displayed foreign brands.
</P>
<P>
He said TBL was at present commanding 80 percent of the market
share, up from 30 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the government's support, TBL shareholders have
revealed a massive three-year expansion program, where up to 65
million US dollars is to be invested, the board chairman added.
</P>
<P>
According to Bomani, if all goes well, the additional
investment was likely to double the firm's annual production from
55 million liters at present to 110 million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was now enjoying dividends and excise
duty income has gone up from 12 billion Tanzanian Shillings (TSH)
(about 19.3 million US dollars) a year in 1993 to 48 billion TSHs
(about 77.4 miilion US dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
This implies that the state could earn up to 100 billion TSHs
(about 161 million US dollars) in excise duty income by the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
