<HEADLINE> Small Scale Quarrying Cause Problems in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Small scale quarrying in Zambia is
causing serious environmental problems and should be urgently
addressed, a Zambian environment official has said.
</P>
<P>
The Post newspaper today quoted Willie Kalunga, Inspector of
the Environmental Council of Zambia (ECZ), as saying here on
Wednesday that the quarrying especially in the capital has become
a worrying environmental concern and that little seems to be done
to stop it.
</P>
<P>
He said quarries are usually left uncovered after excavation
leaving water to collect and eventually turning them into
breeding areas for differenct diseases while the ground water
used for drinking is also contaminated.
</P>
<P>
The stone crushers themselves are exposed to a lot of health
risks as they inhale many rock particles during their work, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said a standing committee comprising members from the ECZ,
the Ministry of Mines, the Lusaka City Council and the
Eenvironment Ministry has been set up to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said that an alternative to the quarrying has
been elusive for some time because most of the people involved in
the activity are poor and depend on it for their livelihood.
enditem

