<HEADLINE> Rebels See Hope for Resuming Peace Talks With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Muslim rebel group said today it
has seen hope for the resumption of peace negotiations with the
Philippine government with the mediation of a Muslim leader in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Mura, vice chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF), said the group also saw hope for the normalization of the
peace and order condition in central Mindanao after talks
Wednesday with Governor of the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM) Nur Misuari.
</P>
<P>
Murad, who is in charge of MILF military affairs, disclosed
that MILF leaders met Misuari in its biggest camp, Camp Abubakar
in Barira municipality in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Misuari was earlier asked by President Fidel Ramos to help
bring back rebel negotiators to the negotiating table. The MILF
suspended the peace talks late last month after its second biggest
camp in Cotabato province was seized by the military.
</P>
<P>
Describing the meeting with Misuari as "brotherly," Murad said
Misuari's mediation was welcomed by the MILF leadership.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Misuari and the MILF leadership laid down a
number of proposals to facilitate the resumption of the
negotiations, according to Murad.
</P>
<P>
Murad said the MILF reiterated its conditions for reopening the
peace talks, which include the pull-out of military troops in
"MILF-controlled areas", the cessation of military operations
against the MILF and the return of evacuees to their original
places.
</P>
<P>
Murad stressed that the MILF's position on the pull-out of
government troops and the cessation of military operations is
non-negotiable.
</P>
<P>
He said Misuari promised to bring their proposals to the
attention of Ramos and to convince the military to stop launching
offensive operations against the MILF.
</P>
<P>
But Murad refused to reveal the details regarding the proposals
made by Misuari, saying the MILF's Central Committee has not yet
discussed the matter.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, who is also chairman of the former rebel group, the
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), was elected the ARMM
governor after the MNLF forged a peace deal with Manila last
September.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the MNLF, refused to be
included in the MNLF-government peace accord and began its own
peace talks with the government this January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
