<HEADLINE> Nigeria Has One Million Blind Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- At least one million Nigerians are
blind as a result of various eye-related diseases, according to
the Ophthalmological Society of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A recent announcement of the society estimated that some 200,000
more Nigerians become blind because of the same causative factors, the
daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figures indicated that among the country's projected 100
million population, there is one blind persons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about three million Nigerians are visually impaired and
cannot engage in productive employment as a result of eye diseases.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort to control the problem, the society is going
to organize free eye screening exercise in Lagos, the populous
economic center of the country, in the second half of this month.
</P>
<P>
A symposium will be held later this month to educate the
public on how to prevent blindness, the society said.
</P>
<P>
According to the society, three out of four blind persons need not
to have gone blind as the causes of their blindness can either have
been prevented or cured.
</P>
<P>
It listed the leading causes of blindness in Nigeria as cataracts
glaucoma, onchocerciasis (commonly known as river blindness),
trachoma, corneal blindness from measles and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
Other causes include injuries and foreign bodies as well as harmful
traditional practice.  enditem

