<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down Despite Jobs Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Investors seeking refuge from
gold's recent share market rout moved into banking and insurance
stocks today, prompting a late rally which saw the Australian
share market finish only moderately down.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade, the all ordinaries index was down 1.7
points at 2,694.4 staging a sharp turnaround after the release of
June jobs data which sparked renewed hopes of a possible easing of
official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
A Sydney-based broker said the market firmed after the release
of Australian Bureau of Statistics data showing total employment
rose 11,900 to 8.3927 million in June.
</P>
<P>
"That definitely turned things around today, however, I think a
cut in interest rates is still a possibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 14.5 points down at 1,430.1,
while the all industrials index finished 12.1 points higher at
4,318.8.
</P>
<P>
The bank index rose 82.3 points to 5,049.5 with ANZ Bank
jumping 29 cents to close at 10.10 Australian dollars, Westpac
Bank was up 15 cents and Commonwealth piled on 23 cents to end the
day at 16.26 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among other industrials, soft drink giant Coca-Cola Amatil
plunged a massive 7.24 percent to 15.12 Australian dollars, and
Fosters Brewing Group lifted eight cents to 2.61 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks saw further recovery with the sector closing up 9.5
points at 1,239.4, while in Sydney gold bullion was trading at
318.80 US dollars an ounce from Wednesday's 316.00.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 322.99 million shares traded worth
838.38 million Australian dollars (628.78 million US dollars).
</P>
