<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar closes Weaker After Job Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian money markets
interpreted today's labor force data as adding to the case for an
official rate cut, and drove the local currency down.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 74.33 US cents, down from its
74.42 US cents finish yesterday, after bottoming at 74.10 shortly
after the release of the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS)
June labor data.
</P>
<P>
The ABS data released this morning showed that in June total
employment rose 11,900 compared with an average market forecast of
a 30,000 increase.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate was 8.5 percent, down from 8.8 percent
previously.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank's foreign exchange manager Wayne Raven said,
expectation of an interest rate cut had moved from "if" to "when"
and that local unit's outlook showed a bias which was "very much
on the downside".
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia last cut its official cash rate
to 5.5 percent on May 23, which brought it in line with the
equivalent official rate in the United States.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rate, the Australian dollar closed at 83.74 from
83.94 against the yen and at 1.3113 from 1.3092 against the mark.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
