<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Although the final communique of the NATO Madrid summit did
not mention when or whether France would return to the military
integrated structure of the military alliance, it is clear that the
United States is pushing France to make a decision before the end of
the year, because all the key posts of NATO in Europe, which France
expects to take, will have been taken by other countries by then.
</P>
<P>
-- On the fifth day of fighting between Cambodia's royalist
forces supporting First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh and those
supporting Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, Cambodia was plunged a
little more into chaos on Wednesday. Thousands of foreigners, most
of them from Southeast Asian countries, were waiting for evacuation
on the Pochentong internatinal airport of Phnom Penh, where a
commando from Thailand was deployed to secure the evacuations.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French experts estimate that public deficit of France will
stand at 3.5 to 4 percent of its GDP by the end of the year, if
the government does not sell its 37.5 billion franc (6.3 billion
U.S. dollar) stocks of the France Telecom telecommunication
corporation.
</P>
<P>
-- The French Minister of National Education, Research and
Technology, Claude Allegre, said that he plans to develop an
education industry in France, and suggested that all universities
make obligatory one hour of philosophy teaching for first-year
college students.  
</P>
