<HEADLINE> Nigerian Foreign Minister Leaves for UN on Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi
left here yesterday for New York to brief the United Nations
on the Sierra Leone situation.
</P>
<P>
As the head of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) Committee of Four on Sierra Leone, Ikimi is expected to seek
support from the UN Security Council for ECOWAS's initiative to restore
the legitimate government of outsted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi's trip was ordered by ECOWAS Chairman, Nigerian Head
of State General Sani Abacha, during Abacha's meeting with the committee
in Abuja on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Four on Sierra Leone was composed of the
foreign ministers of Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire to
deal with the Sierra Leone crisis in the wake of the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sierra Leonean troops loyal to coup leader Major Johnny
Paul Koromah yesterday launched an attack on the west African
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) controlling the Lungi international
airport near Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The attack was reportedly aimed at silencing a radio station
believed to be based in the airport, through which outsted president
Kabbah has in the few days called on the Koromah government to step down.
</P>
<P>
The trading of heavy gun fire at the airport caused casualties on
both sides and sent thousands of residents nearby on fleeing,
according to reports reaching here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
