<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Helping China's Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- China's 4.5-million-ha of cotton
fields are doing better than last year, with the blossoming stage
coming five days earlier in major cotton producing areas, a good
sign for this year's harvest.
</P>
<P>
Vice-minister of Agriculture Bai Zhijian told a recent meeting
on cotton production in Urumqi, the capital of the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, that plastic sheeting was applied to nearly 60
percent of this year's cotton acreage, and transplanted seedlings
were used for 40 percent of the total growing area.
</P>
<P>
Hybrid-seed areas accounted for more than 90 percent of the
land planted, which is a further guarantee of a good harvest, Bai
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China began a nationwide campaign to promote cotton
production through science and technology, and managed to raise
its per-ha average yield from 7,860 kg to 8,895 kg.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, which is China's largest cotton producer, harvested
more than 900,000 tons of cotton last year, with a per-ha average
output of 11,760 kg, the highest in the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
