<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Takes Measures to Protect Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Since Thailand announced its
adoption of a managed float policy on the baht on July 3, the
Philippine monetary authorities have been taking measures to fend
the peso off spillover negative effects from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The baht's devaluation sparked turmoil in Asian financial
market. Some market analysts predicted that the Philippine peso
would be the next target for speculators, citing the many things
the two countries' economies have in common.
</P>
<P>
On July 3, volume turnover at the Philippine Dealing System
(PDS), the country's electronic currencies exchanges, hit an
all-time high of 1.049 billion U.S. dollars, almost five times as
high as the market's average daily volume for the past six months.
</P>
<P>
It was a clear sign that the peso was under speculative
attacks, analysts said. The same attacks, which came out of fears
that the peso may devalue, also sent the country's stock market
tumbling again.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank quickly responded to the attacks.
While heavily selling dollars to absorb excess pesos, it
immediately raised the closely watched overnight borrowing rate
from 15 to 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
A hike in the overnight rate made it more expensive for banks
to hold onto dollars as the same amount of funds, when converted
into the peso, would earn much more in the overnight facility of
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank's timely intervention succeeded. It curbed a sharp
depreciation of the peso, sending the dollar-peso exchange rate
back to normal at one dollar to 26.37 pesos.
</P>
<P>
During the past 12 months, the peso has been fluctuating within
a very narrow band range of about 0.5 to 1 percent, averaging one
dollar to 26.4 pesos.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine financial market has become very
sensitive to any speculation after much turmoil due to some bad
news from the outside, especially from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, a Singapore newspaper quoted Philippine finance
chief Roberto de Ocampo as saying Manila favored a slight
devaluation of the peso, putting the currency once again under
heavy attack.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign exchange traded at the PDS quickly rose
to 633 million Monday morning. To show its determination to defend
the peso, the central bank again raised the overnight rate to a
two-year high of 30 percent from 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time in a week that the bank increased the
overnight rate. Earlier this year, the rate stood at only 7.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The last time the rate hit 30 percent was in 1995 at the height
of the Mexican currency crisis. Because of the bank's swift
intervention, the country's entire banking system and the peso
remained steady.
</P>
<P>
The bank's action once again proved successful on Monday. But
meanwhile, a controversy erupted between businessmen and the
government about the country's foreign exchange policy.
</P>
<P>
The central bank and the Philippine government have been
favoring a stable exchange rate and even a slight appreciation of
the peso. They insist that the current dollar-peso exchange rate
is determined by market forces.
</P>
<P>
Exporters and economists, however, said the peso is overvalued
and undermined the competitiveness of Filipino products in the
global markets. They recommended a 2- to 6-percent devaluation of
the peso against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they said the current exchange rate is not
market-determined since the government has been letting the peso
traded at a very narrow band through frequent intervention.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos has expressed interest in reviewing the
foreign exchange policy, but said "not at this time." He wants the
baht, whose movement continues to feed speculative attacks on the
peso, to stabilize first.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Ramos is wary that there might be a massive devaluation of
the peso when it (review of the foreign exchange policy) is done
at this time," sources close to the president said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Philippines has successfully kept the foreign
exchange rate stable, but that does not mean that the peso has
been safe. Since Monday, the Manila Stock Exchange index has been
nose-diving on rising fears that the peso may devalue.
</P>
<P>
The index fell by 4 percent to a two-year low of 2589.2 points
on Wednesday. And today, the decline continued as the local bourse
plummeted 78 points more to another record low.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said that if the trend continues, the peso
would face mounting pressure and force the central bank to take
more measures to avoid the breakdown of the peso.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
