<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Bourse Falls to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Composite Index
(Phisix) fell to a new low today despite the government's vow to
use all means to stabilize the country's foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The 30-stock Phisix, the main index of the Philippine Stock
Exchange, plunged by 78.05 points or 3.01 percent to close at
2,511.15, the lowest since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Phisix fell 109.46 points, the biggest
one-day loss since April, after investors opted to sell their
shares for fears that the Philippine Central Bank may devalue the
country's currency peso.
</P>
<P>
The country's currency market has been volatile this week
because of rumors about a devaluation of the peso after Thailand's
currency was floated last week.
</P>
<P>
Traders said investors remained worried over the prospect of
the peso although the central bank Wednesday ruled out the
possibility of depreciating the peso and pledged to take all means
to protect it.
</P>
<P>
At today's trading session, the total market volume shrank to
5.53 billion shares from Wednesday's 6.56 billion. Total value
turnover was 2.67 billion pesos (101.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All sub-indices ended on the downside except the oil sector
which rose 0.06 points to finish at 5.48. The
commercial-industrial and mining sectors continued to register
biggest drops after closing at 3,428.53 (-93.95) and 3,618.52
(-61.9) respectively.
</P>
<P>
The broader All Shares Index also recorded a substantial
21.83-point decline to close at 823.42. Losers continued to
outnumber gainers 105 to 25, with 50 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
