<HEADLINE> Remains of Dutch Tourists Flown Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Dutch airliner took off in Egypt
early this morning flying back the bodies of eight Dutch tourists
who were killed in a road accident in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place on Tuesday afternoon when their bus
collided with a trailer truck on the road linking Egypt's two
famous tourist cities of Aswan and Abu Simbel.
</P>
<P>
Eight Dutch nationals and an Egyptian were killed while 15
others were injured, including eight Dutch, two Belgian and five
Egyptian.
</P>
<P>
The injured Dutch tourists were flown back to their country on
Wednesday afternoon aboard a specially-equipped urgent treatment
and evacuation plane sent from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The planes took off from the southern city of Aswan, about 900
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Every day thousands of foreign tourists swarm to Egypt's
southern resorts that are famous for their pharaonic relics and
spectacular landscape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
