<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: Iran to Deal Severely with Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Interior Minister Ali
Mohammad Besharati has said that his country will deal severely
with foreign offenders, the Iranian news agency (IRNA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The official IRNA report quoted the Interior Minister as saying
Wednesday that foreign refugees breaking the (Iranian) law "will
be severely dealt with in accordance with agreements reached with
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)."
</P>
<P>
Besharati made the statement in response to the case in which
an Afghan man was accused of killing 11 Iranian women in a stolen
car.
</P>
<P>
The criminal, identified as Abdullah Abdurrahman, 28, was
arrested last week on charges of the murdering 11 Iranian women.
</P>
<P>
Posing himself as a night-time cab driver, he would drive his
female passengers outside the city to the dark wilderness west of
Tehran and beat or stab them to death and then took their
valuables and set their corpses on fire.
</P>
<P>
The case has aroused wide public attention in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The English daily Iran News said, in its editorial published
today, that "such criminals and their crimes become
earth-shattering when the laxness of a country's law enforcement
becomes an evident and integral part of the daily violation of the
national code."
</P>
<P>
The daily called on the parliament to make a thorough
investigation about the slackness of the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Prosecutor General Morteza Moqtadayee vowed that the
Afghan criminal will be punished to the fullest extent of the
law, i.e. execution or death by hanging, the capital punishment
of the Islamic country.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister admitted that it is the ministry's duty
to insure discipline and security at the borders, combat
smugglers and drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
But the minister did not specify what kind of measures Iran
will take to deal with foreign refugees, who constitute one of
the major sources for the increasing crimes in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that in the country there are 1.28 million Afghans,
490,000 Iraqis and some refugees from other states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- United Nations' coordinator in Iraq said Wednesday that the
Iraqi government submitted to the U.N. a draft plan on supplying
Iraqis with foodstuffs during the coming six months within the
context of the oil-for-food agreement.
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa left here for Tunisia
Wednesday night on a five-day tour that will also take him to
Algeria. The meetins of the Egyptian-Tunisian committee will
discuss means of boosting economic and trade cooperation between
the two countries and joint action to set up a free trade zone.
</P>
