<HEADLINE> No Clean Water for One Third of S. Africans: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Twelve million people,
nearly one third of the population in South Africa, have no
access to clear water and 21 million are without sewerage
services, according to a survey by the Department of Water
Affairs and Forestry.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Sowetan quoted spokesman of the department
Thuso Ramaema as reporting that the government did not have
enough resources to deliver sustainable water services to all
communities and had to rely on the private sector to "get the job
done quickly".
</P>
<P>
Ramaema denied accusations by the South African Municipal Workers
Union that the government was privatizing water and sewerage services.
</P>
<P>
"Government money is being used to pay for the water
infrastructure and on completion of construction and training of
local people to maintain and operate the pumps, the infrastructure
will be passed on to local governemnt," he said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa lacks water resouces. Ever since it took power in
1994, the Government of National Unity led by President Nelson
Mandela has been making great effort to solve the water problem.
</P>
<P>
For now, the South African government has allocated 50 million
Rand (11.36 million U.S. dollars) for nationwide water project
construction. Constructions of water projects in 693 areas across
the country are due to be completed before the year 2000,
government sources said early this year. enditem

