<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US reassured Egypt of No Change in Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration has
reassured Egypt that it has no plan to cut off its annual 2.1
billion U.S. dollars aid to Egypt in the coming fiscal year, The
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reassurances from the U.S. side came during the
Egyptian-U.S. Partnership Subcommittee meetings which were held
in Washington this week and attended by Egyptian Minister of
Trade and Supplies Ahmed Goweili and Minister of Finance Mohi
Eddin el-Gharib.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate Appropriations Subcommittee recommended in
mid-June to end allocations to Egypt as a punishment to its
"harsh approach" to the Mideast peace-making.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it upheld maintaining Israel's 3 billion dollars
grant and creating a 250-million-dollar fund for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Goweili said that the U.S. would offer Egypt technical
assistance in the areas of information technology, finance
services and communications to benefit from opportunities offered
by the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economic assistance to Egypt amounted to 21 billion
dollars between 1975 and 1996. At first, the aid took the forms
of repayable loans and unrepayable grants. But since 1982, most
of the aid was made in grants.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the U.S. called on Egypt to increase the
economic growth rates from the current 5 percent to 7 percent in
the coming years through booming up investment by offering
incentives and facilities and reducing custom duties.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also discussed necessary measures to set up
a joint free trade zone and increase Egyptian export of
ready-made clothes and textiles to the U.S. markets as well as
means to protect U.S. intellectual property rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
