<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Drafts New Labor Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has drafted a new labor
law in a bid to boost benefits for employees in the country's
private sector where more than 80 percent of the workers are
expatriates.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported today that the law, to be submitted to the
Cabinet and then to the Kuwaiti National Assembly for approval,
will come into force before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The labor law, drafted by Kuwaiti Ministry of Social Affairs
and Labor, calls for increasing public holidays, sick leave and
work injury benefits for employees.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, annual leave for employees in the first five
years will be increased from the existing 14 days to 21 days, and
from 21 days to 30 days in the subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
It will allow the setting up of special recruitment agencies to
provide the needed employees to businessmen from inside and
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to eradicate the rampant visa smuggling in Kuwait,
the law bans employers from hiring expatriates without permission
from the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor.
</P>
<P>
It also forbids businessmen from employing laborers from
outside Kuwait and failing to provide them with jobs. Violators
will face a jail term up to three years and a fine of 16,500
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The law also bans teenagers before the age of 15 from working
in the private sector and allows those above 15 to work after
obtaining a special permission from the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently has more than 1 million foreign laborers and
the government has been striving to increase the percentage of
local laborers in the private sector as well as in the state-owned
economic sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0138 </DOCNO>
