<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Private Entrepreneurs Helping The Needy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of Chinese
private entrepreneurs are joining the effort to help needy people
escape the bonds of poverty.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 private entrepreneurs in Shanxi province in north
China have spent almost 100 million yuan on 45 aid-the-poor
projects that helped 9,500 rural laborers find jobs and provided
training for 12,000 farmers.
</P>
<P>
The entrepreneurs themselves had benefited from the reform and
opening-up policy, which encouraged people to make money, or, as a
popular saying goes, "To be rich is glorious".
</P>
<P>
Li Anming, the chairman of the Antai International Enterprise
(Group) Co. Ltd. in Jiexiu city in Shanxi Province, is one
example, having donated 13 million yuan to help people in poor
areas and to provide welfare funds.
</P>
<P>
"We are voluntarily throwing ourselves into the anti-poverty
work, as a way of paying back what we have got from the good
policy," Li explained.
</P>
<P>
Liang Wenhai, chairman of the Shanxi Huanhai Industrial
Co. Ltd., followed in Li's tracks, and is expected to spend 30
million yuan on helping raise the standard of living in Hongdu
Village in Zuoquan county, where villagers' per capita income was
only 290 yuan, and on opening businesses in a poor county in
southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Chinese have become prosperous since the late
1970s, but there are still 58 million poor people in rural parts
of China, which is still fighting a nationwide poverty relief
campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
