<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Service Improved in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A study of 25 airports in China
and 3,500 air routes used by 16 airlines has shown improvements in
the country's airline service, according to Chen Ziye, an official
of the Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
An average score of 82.3 points out of a possible 100 was given
by airline passengers who were asked about service provided by
China's airlines in 1996. This was up from the 79.8-point average
for the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
The "'96 Travelers Talking about Civil Aviation" report, which
was released today, showed that the country's airports got a score
of 80 points, up from 78.7 points.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.3 million copies of the inquiry were handed out and
nearly 27,000 of them were returned, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"Passengers are most satisfied with the service of
stewardesses, who got 92 points," Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the best airports and airlines are
China Eastern Airlines, Xiamen Airlines, Shenzhen Airlines,
Xiamen's Gaoqi Airport, and Liangjiang Airport in Guilin.
</P>
<P>
The event was sponsored by the China Civil Aviation
Association, the National Civil Aviation Association of Young
Volunteers, and the magazine "China Civil Aviation". 
</P>
</TEXT>
