<HEADLINE> Tanzania Gives Priority to Road Repairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Ministry of
Works has planned to repair 3,600 km of highways and rural roads
this financial year by using the Road Maintenance Fund.
</P>
<P>
Anna Abdallah, Minister of Works, made the statement
Wednesday when moving the 1997/98 budget in the House in Dodoma,
central Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
She said, her ministry would focus on making regular and
periodical repairs on existing roads and clearing clogged sewage
systems and culverts.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has already established a bridge unit to conduct
feasibility studies on all bridges in the country and on how they
could be maintained without foreign aid, she added.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah noted that the bridge unit would also build its
capacity to handle emergency cases of collapsed bridges without
waiting for allocated funds.
</P>
<P>
She told the House that her ministry has got three
computerized roads weighing scales which would be installed along
the TANZAM highway to check overloading.
</P>
<P>
In this financial year, the Ministry of Works would install
new weighing scales at Msamvu in Morogoro, Mafinga in Iringa and
at Tunduma-Zambia border to save roads from damages caused by
overloading, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
