<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Workshop on Promotion of Rural Microfinance Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Easing and eliminating poverty is
a major task in China's development plan and is an ongoing basic
policy of the Chinese government, a senior Chinese official said
at today's opening ceremony of the First National
Consultation/Workshop on the Promotion of Rural Microfinance in
China.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the gathering in Beijing, Yang Rudai,
vice-chairman of Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference National Committee, said that it is a strategic goal of
the Chinese government to solve the food and clothing issue of the
poor people in China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the reform and opening-up drive in the late
1970s, the Chinese government has carried out its large-scale
poverty alleviation and development campaign in an organized
manner, and taken a series of special policies and targeted
measures. For example, specialized agencies for poverty relief
have been set up and input into the project has increased.
</P>
<P>
These steps have produced remarkable results, as the number of
poor people without food and clothing has dropped from 250 million
in 1978 to 58 million in 1996, and the proportion of the Chinese
poor population in the world total has decreased from one fourth
to one twentieth, Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
Poverty alleviation through credit is an effective way of
speeding up poverty reduction and development, Yang noted, saying
that as a policy bank of the Chinese government, the Agricultural
Development Bank of China (ADBC) has effectively practiced the
work of poverty alleviation through credit and made a significant
contribution to the job of wiping out poverty in China's rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
To improve its results in the area, Yang pointed out that China
needs to strengthen international exchanges and cooperation and
expand its opening-up.
</P>
<P>
Yang noted that he hopes the international participants and
experts attending the meeting will freely exchange views and find
an approach to the worldwide problem.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar, jointly sponsored by ADBC and the Asia
Pacific Rural and Agricultural Credit Association (APRACA) and the
German Agency for Technical Cooperation, is designed to brainstorm
possibilities for worldwide poverty alleviation through rural
credit.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun and State Councillor Chen
Junsheng each sent congratulatory letters to the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Experts from Germany, India, Indonesia, China and other
countries, and representatives of some foreign countries in
Beijing participated in the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yuanliang, president of ADBC, Mohd Rosli Abdul Aziz, former
chairman of APRACA and president of the Agricultural Bank of
Malaysia attended the opening ceremony and made speeches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Developing Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province can give credit to advanced technology for the rapid
development of animal husbandry programs.
</P>
<P>
The Heilongjiang Livestock Research Institute, the sole body of
its kind for comprehensive research on livestock in the province,
has applied up to 70 percent of its findings to animal-raising,
which has earned about 40 billion yuan in economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, the institute has achieved 146 recognized
scientific and technological findings, 14 of which are up to State
level. Scientific personnel in the institute have helped breed
seven new strains of livestock and had remarkable success in the
development of fodder compound and improved strains.
</P>
<P>
So far, the provincial animal husbandry has generated 14.5 billion
yuan in output value a year, accounting for a third of the local
agricultural total. The province now has nearly one million milk
cows in stock, leading the country in the output of milk and
dairy products. The per capita egg consumption in the province
stands at 25.6 kg, 1.61 times the national average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
