<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Rhinoceros Fossil Found in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A fossil of the skull and neck
bones of a two-horned rhinoceros has been unearthed in Xiaoyi in
north China's Shanxi Province, proving that the enormous creature
inhabited the area in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The fossil was discovered by a local farmer who was digging
sand in the city's suburban Huqi Mountain.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the fossil belongs to a rhinoceros which lived in
the area more than two million years ago. Fossil of the two-horned
rhinoceros have seldom been found in the country.
</P>
<P>
The fossil of the rhinoceros' upper and lower jaws, neck and
ribs are about half a meter long each and all its teeth remained
intact.
</P>
<P>
Scientists and workers, organized by the city authorities,
removed 20,000 sq meters of earth and stones before they dug
the rhino fossil and those of other animals out of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
"We still expect to find the fossil remains for the rest of the
rhino's body in other parts of the mountain, that have not yet
been excavated," said Zhu Jingyi, an archeologist and director of
the city's museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
