<HEADLINE> World's First Seismograph Restored In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The world's first seismograph,
which was invented 1,800 years ago, was recently restored in
Zhengzhou, capital of Henan province, and the hometown of the
inventor.
</P>
<P>
The original seismograph was invented in 138 B.C. by Zhang
Heng, a famous ancient Chinese scientist. It accurately reported
an earthquake 854 kilometers away and has generally been
recognized as the ancestor of the seismograph.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Tourist Item Co. Ltd. of Zhengzhou has spent several
years restoring the Zhang Heng Seismograph. The bronze instrument
is 2.96 meters high, 2.68 meters in diameter, and shapeed like an
ancient Chinese wine vessel. Experts have affirmed that in size,
appearance, structure, and function, it fits the description given
in historical accounts.
</P>
<P>
The restored seismograph is obviously important as a
masterpiece of ancient Chinese technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
