<HEADLINE> Zambian Leather Products Enter Southern African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian leather products company in
Lusaka, Bimzi, has penetrated the southern African markets by selling
its products in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Zambia Daily Mail today quoted the company's
Sales Executive Belina Tembo as saying that her company is saving the
country foreign exchange through export of leather products to
Mozambique, Namibia, Botswana and Malawi.
</P>
<P>
She, however, declined to disclose the volume of exports to those
countries, but said that the goods include leather jackets, handbags,
footballs, wallets, belts and leather folders. The company is
working towards the production of foodware as soon as feasibility
studies are completed.
</P>
<P>
Bimzi has been in operation since 1979. It uses about 90 percent
of local raw materials with the exception of zippers and buckles
which are imported.
</P>
<P>
Belina Tembo said that competition, which is growing under the
liberalization policy, is helping the company to improve quality and
meet international standards. With a workforce of less than 100
people and already producing quality leather products, Bimzi is
set to meet the challenges of the competitive world trade. enditem
