<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestine Agree on Gaza Airport Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and Palestinian Minister of Planning and International
Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath met in Tel Aviv late on Wednesday night
in an effort to solve major overdue issues.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers, with U.S. and Egyptian officials looking on,
agreed to expedite operations of the Palestinian International
Airport at Dahaniya in the Gaza Strip, according to a report of
the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The three-hour meeting took place at the residence of Egyptian
ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny. U.S. ambassador Martin Indyk was
also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also reached an understanding that talks on the
Gaza sea port and "safe passage" between the Gaza Strip and West
Bank will resume next week. Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy is
expected to form a team for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai told Sha'ath that the Palestinians may start
introducing electronic equipments the airport needs, but the
airport will not open until security arrangements are finalized.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli Defense Ministry statement was quoted as saying that
the meeting was efficient and proceeded in a good atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The three issues in question were supposed to have been solved,
together with Israeli troops withdrawal from Hebron, in accordance
with the Oslo peace accord signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the rightwing Likud government has delayed it under the
pretext of security concerns. Talks over the issues came to a stop
after Israel began construction of Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has declared that
political talks will resume on the condition that Israel suspends
Har Homa building and stops expansion of the settlements.
</P>
<P>
Israel replied that it wants to continue the peace process,
but rejected the idea on Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The Mordechai-Sha'ath meeting was believed to be part of the
U.S.-Egyptian effort to restart the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
