<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast China Province Boosting Aquaculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's coastal province
of Fujian has set itself the goal of 3.65 million tons of aquatic
products annually by the turn of the century, with more than 39.5
billion yuan in output value in aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
It already led the country with per capita consumption of
nearly 86 kg of aquatic products in 1996, four times the national
average, and ranked third in the country, after Guangdong and
Shandong provinces, in production, with 2.84 million tons of
aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
The province is rich in marine resources and in fact
administers a greater sea area than land. Its aquaculture
contributes more than four-fifths of the output value of local
marine fisheries. Along its 3,300-km coastline there are 125 bays,
and more than 1,200 islands and islets. It has 125,000 sq km of
fishing areas, 190,000 ha. of seaside areas, and more than 410,000
ha. of shallow water areas.
</P>
<P>
Fujian had 90,000 ha. for marine culture in 1996, nearly 70,000
ha. of which was for shellfish and seaweed farming. Output of
shellfish and seaweed is expected to rise to 797,000 tons this
year from 719,000 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000 the province is expected to earn one billion
US dollars from exports of aquatic products, a big leap from the
650 million US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Also by then, nearly half of the province's marine production,
or 670,000 tons, will come from deep sea fishing, while processed
aquatic products will account for two-fifths of the local total
seafood products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
