<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Migration Program Lifts 130,000 People Out of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Qingyuan, a poverty-stricken
area in north Guangdong, China's wealthiest province, is one step
closer toward its long-cherished dream of becoming rich.
</P>
<P>
A massive migration program that started three years ago has
put 130,000 people, or 85 percent of the poorest people in the
region, to work on new tillable land that enable them to earn a
living.
</P>
<P>
They formerly lived in mountainous, sandy areas which are not
suitable for farming. Now working on the 8,000-plus hectares of
wasteland contracted from the local government, each of them can
earn an average 1,180 yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
So far the government has provided 137 million yuan for the
program. Most of the money was used to build new houses, the rest
went to building schools and training centers to provide children
with proper education and young people with technical training.
</P>
<P>
With the help of agro-technicians, the migrants have learned to
grow high-yielding rice, fruit trees and vegetables on the new
land.
</P>
<P>
Like the rest of the country, Guangdong has pledged to
eradicate poverty by the end of this century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
