<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Public Leaders Facing Corruption Urged to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral has asked those in public life who face corruption
charges to resign forthwith on moral grounds, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is so far the clearest signal from the prime minister that
Bihar Chief Minister Laloo Prasad Yadav should step down after the
Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) charged him in a major
corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
Yadav, former president of the ruling Janata Dal, was accused
of being involved in a fodder scandal in which huge sums of state
funds for purchasing fodder were embezzled.
</P>
<P>
Defying public opinion urging him to quit the post of Bihar
chief minister, Yadav floated a new party on Saturday, plunging
the two-month-old Gujral government into serious crisis.
</P>
<P>
Janata Dal, which used to be the biggest constituent of the
13-party United Front, lost its dominance in the ruling front
after the split.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Gujral, who is also from Janata Dal, has been
under great pressure that he should force the resignation of Yadav
as chief minister of Bihar, the second largest state in India.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a rally in India's Uttar Pradesh Wednesday, Gujral
said those holding public offices must subject themselves to the
test of probity and when people in public offices face charges of
corruption, they are left with no alternative but to give up their
office.
</P>
<P>
However he did not name any names.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
