<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Help Harness Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Over the next three years,
Shanghai will build three major projects to help harness the Taihu
Lake, one of China's five largest lakes, according to Xia Keqiang,
deputy mayor of the municipality.
</P>
<P>
A leading group in charge of the construction has been
established for the three projects, which were decided this May at
a fourth meeting of the State Council on harnessing the Huaihe
River and the Taihu Lake. Cost is estimated at 1.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Construction will involve embankments, water-diversion
facilities for a 23.5-km-long river course, dredging and expansion
of a 5.1-km river course, and flood control facilities on the
upper reaches of the Huangpu.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory work for construction is to be finished this year
and actual construction work will begin soon.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, an important part of the Taihu Lake Valley, has often
suffered from flood damage there. An effort has been made to
prevent major flood damage since 1991, when a severe flood hit the
Taihu Lake Basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspension of Seven Ordinances Necessary: HK Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- It's necessary and reasonable to
suspend operation of seven ordinances which were hastily enacted
at the last session of the Legislative Council under British Hong
Kong authorities, commentaries published by Hong Kong newspapers
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Provisions (Suspension of Operation) Bill,
tabled by the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
Government, passed the first and second readings on Wednesday at a
full sitting of the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
That the last Legislative Council adopted a batch of ordinances
only several days before the establishment of the HKSAR
represented an attitude which was far from responsible for the
Hong Kong people, a commentary carried by Hong Kong Commercial
Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Five of the ordinances are labor-related, but they didn't go
through any consultation or receive any examination by the Labor
Advisory Board, the commentary said. If kept effective in the
HKSAR, they will have an adverse impact on the society and will be
detrimental to Hong Kong's prosperity and stability, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR Government took a prudent approach toward the
ordinances by proposing suspension of their operation, said the
commentary, adding the proposal embodied respect for and
safeguarding of Hong Kong's legal system.
</P>
<P>
The last Legislative Council made hasty legislation during its
last days only to force the HKSAR Government into accepting these
pieces of legislation. The HKSAR Government, however, is entitled
to reexamining the ordinances adopted by the last Legislative
Council, the commentary pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao's commentary said, the last Legislative Council, by
adopting many labor-related ordinances shortly before July 1, was
not striving for the rights and interests of employees as it had
said, instead it was challenging the PLC and creating troubles for
the HKSAR Government.
</P>
<P>
Correct handling of the relationship between employers and
employees is quite important to Hong Kong, the commentary said.
However, the five ordinances adopted by the last Legislative
Council had an adverse effect on the labor relations, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is an international business hub with many countries
investing here. Therefore, creating a favorable investment
environment will enhance their confidence and play a vital role in
maintaining Hong Kong's prosperity and stability, the commentary
noted.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang attended Wednesday's PLC
sitting. At a media session at the Legislative Council Building,
Tsang said, the five ordinances "might affect Hong Kong's
competitiveness and I believe this is certainly a very bad
development in the early days of the SAR." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
