<HEADLINE> Cooperation the Best Policy for Serb Crisis: Milosevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Serbian President of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia Slobodan Milosevic said today that
cooperation was the best way to resolve the political conflict
vexing the Republic of Srpska in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
His views were shared by Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member of
Bosnia's multi-ethnic collective presidency, who held talks with
the president here today.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders believed cooperation between the parties concerned
could lead the country out of the political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also stressed the importance of thoroughly
implementing the Dayton agreement, adding that curbing various
criminal crimes and the grey economy was the government's top
priority after the war.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said both parties in the present conflict should make
some concessions and try to seek the common ground they should
share, according to the constitution and the Dayton accord.
</P>
<P>
President of the Republic of Srpska Biljana Plavsic and
hardliners led by Krajisnik have been locked in a crisis for more
than a week following Plavsic's accusations that Krajisnik and
Radovan Karazdic were involved in large-scale corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
