<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Official Optimistic Over Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Investment (BOI)
of!!Thailand expects that new investment in the second half of
this year will match that of the first half.
</P>
<P>
BOI Secretary-General Staporn Kavitanon also expects direct
foreign investment to return to normal over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that it will take time for the economy to
recover but everything should return to normal within two years.
</P>
<P>
He said the positive effects from the baht float since July 2
will not be felt in terms of foreign direct investment over the
next six months, even though some investors now have more
confidence in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
To promote new investment projects, the BOI announced on
Wednesday that it will exempt import duties on machinery used by
36 industries.
</P>
<P>
Among those sectors that will be entitled to duty exemptions on
imported machinery are mineral smelting, footwear and pieces,
precious stone cutting, jewelry, sports equipment, electronic
toys, optical lenses, medical equipment, machine tools,
shipbuilding and repairing, machinery production, electrical
vehicle production, petrochemical products, industrial waste
treatment, pulp and paper and power plants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
