<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Dead, 18 Missing in Japanese Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A massive flash flood and landslide
triggered by torrential rains in Kagoshima Prefecture,
southwestern Japan, killed seven people, and left 18 missing and
13 injured today, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred along the Harihara River in the city of
Lzumi, soon after midnight. It buried 15 homes and about 40
residents under mud and rocks.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains forced police and fire fighters to halt rescue
operations because of the possibility of a second landslide. A
total of 427 millimeters of rain was recorded in the city between
last Monday and 5 o'clock this morning.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains also caused a landslide in the city of
Minamata, in Kumamoto Prefecture next to Kagoshima Prefecture, on
Wednesday. It buried nine people under earth, all of whom were
rescued, police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
