<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Finds American Shoe Ad Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai House Committee on
Religious Affairs considers a television advertisement in the
United States as offensive to Buddhists and has decided to draw
the attention of the U.S. Congress to it.
</P>
<P>
A TV commercial by an American sports shoe company features
young monks who are asked to join in a basketball game and it
turns out the whole group wear the company's shoes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Religious Affairs Department of the Thai
government asked the Thai ambassador to the United States to
approach the shoe manufacturer to stop using the advertisement but
to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Similar ads have appeared in several magazines.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the first time American manufacturers have
offended Buddhism with such commercial ads," Committee Chairman
Den Tohmeena said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will see to it that the manufacturer suspends the ads, and
we will explain to Americans how much Thai Buddhists respect their
religion and how they find such advertisements offensive," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Den also urged Buddhists in Thailand and foreign countries to
join the protest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
