<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Countries' Debts to Russia Hit $7 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The debts owed by countries of
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) to Russia have
reached 6.786 billion U.S. dollars, including overdue debts and
interests of 1.282 billion.
</P>
<P>
The figures were provided by the Russian Economy Ministry and
the CIS Department for Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The debts excluded 1.624 billion U.S. dollars owed by CIS
nations to Russian corporations, Russian peacekeeping troops and
frontier army, said Dmitri Chegordaev, head of the CIS Inter-State
Monetary Committee, in an interview with the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Out of the debts of 6.786 billion dollars, Ukraine ranks first
among the CIS states, accounting for 3.395 billion, followed by
Kazakhstan with 1.683 billion, Uzbekistan 557 billion and Belarus
700,000, said Chegordaev.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by Russia and other CIS states over
repaying capital with interest, Chegordaev said CIS countries have
to repay the debts including interests between 1999-2008. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
