<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting Giant Panda's Habitats (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The most effective way to protect
the endangered giant panda is to protect their natural habitats,
an official from the Giant Panda Protection Office of China'a
Forestry Ministry told Xinhua in an exclusive interview today.
</P>
<P>
He said that a series of Forestry Ministry and government
department efforts had reduced the threat from the people to the
giant panda's habitat, but because of a lack of funds the
situation is still not as good as it should be.
</P>
<P>
The official made a tour of Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces,
where most of the giant pandas live, and explained that the weak
eco-system in their habitats is now the main threat to the
protection work.
</P>
<P>
"About 1,000 giant pandas in the world are now being separated
into small groups by human activities and highways, and there are
only three to five giant pandas in some of the smallest groups,"
he said, noting that this will lead to serious problems with
inbreeding and species degeneration.
</P>
<P>
He explained that an unstable food supply is another serious
ecological problem for this endangered species, and "What is
worse, bamboo, which is the staple food of the giant panda, have
been dying in large tracts for a period of time."
</P>
<P>
In the '70s and '80s, two serious problems with bamboo caused
the whole nation to get involved in a large-scale
save-the-giant-panda drive.
</P>
<P>
From 1983 to 1996, as many as 183 giant pandas suffering from
illness or malnutrition were found in the wild and saved, and a
large number, after recovering, were released to their natural
habitats.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, since 1992, when the "China Giant Panda and
Habitat Protection Project" was started by the Ministry of
Forestry, 11 natural reserves have been established, bringing the
number of natural reserves for the giant panda to 25.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Forestry Ministry has allocated 64 million
yuan (nearly 8 million US dollars) for the giant panda protection
project, and that, "Our goal is to continue to establish natural
reserves for the giant panda so that their natural habitats can be
put under state protection."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting Giant Panda's Habitat (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the next several years, there will be three new natural
reserves and 17 "green passage ways" linking various natural
reserves established to better protect the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Ministry of Forestry also say that, since
1992, when China increased protection of the giant panda, a number
of timber mills have been shut down and people relocated to reduce
the harmful effects of humans on this endangered species that has
the top state protection.
</P>
<P>
The sources say that, since 1992, forestry departments, which
have a great deal of the responsibility for wildlife protection in
China, have made a greater effort to improve local people's lives
to reduce the pressure 0on the environment.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda protection staff have also turned to science to
look for solutions to breeding and food supply problems of this
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, there have been special funds for research on how
to retard flowering of bamboo to protect its growth. And the
"China Research Center for Giant Panda Protection" in the Wolong
National Nature Reserve in southwest China's Sichuan province, has
produced 16 giant pandas through artificial reproduction over the
past five years, 12 of which survived.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is one of the world's most famous rare species,
and there are only about a thousand estimated to be in existence,
in 32 counties in western China's Shaanxi, Sichuan and Gansu
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Guatemala Allocates $3.3 Million to Arm Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Guatemala will allocate 20
million quetzals (about 3.3 million U.S. dollars) to equip its new
National Civilian Police (PNC) with modern weapons, according to
reports from Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
Second Deputy Interior Minister Amilcar Pantaleon said that the
fund is mainly used to combat ordinary and organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
He explained in detail that with the 20 million quetzals, the
government will purchase vehicles and weapons for the patrol work
of the first 1,200 PNC agents.
</P>
<P>
Those policemen are part of the agreement to strengthen
civilian power and the functions of the army signed between the
government and the former guerrillas in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
