<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Defense Department Calls For More Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian defense department
has called for real increases in defense spending beyond the year
2000 to carry out plans to buy advanced weapons and military
facilities, the national newspaper the Australian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department cites a 270 million U.S. dollar annual shortfall
for three vital planned purchases -- Airborne Early Warning and
Control aircraft, helicopters for the Australian and New Zealand
Army Corps frigates and new offshore patrol vessels, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The department has told a parliamentary committee that "no
funding provision has yet been made for them."
 The paper said the defense department's proposal is certain to be
seen as self-serving, but added that a fierce debate over the
government's spending priorities was expected following budget
cuts that have also reduced the share of outlays for health,
education and social security.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Standing Committee of Foreign Affairs, Defense and
Trade committee is due to start hearing within the next month and
will report well before the next election.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Ian McLachlan, a close friend of Prime
Minister John Howard, has signaled he intends to fight for
increased funding.
</P>
<P>
The report said the defense department will back the bid for
"modest" real increases in the 7.8 billion U.S. dollar defense
budget by revealing details of an internal study showing the cost
of buying weapons systems is increasing by at least 4 percent a
year more than the rate of inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
