<HEADLINE> Brazil to Eliminate Sugar Export Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government
will eliminate quotas on sugar exports starting next year, a
Brazilian official said today.
</P>
<P>
Mauricio Assis, secretary of commodities for the Ministry of
Industry, Commerce and Tourism, said the current sugar quota for
companies authorized by the government is 5.3 million tons,
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the biggest producer and exporter of sugar in the
world. Last year it produced 12 million tons of sugar and exported
more than five million tons.
</P>
<P>
This season's production of sugar cane, estimated at 315
million tons, will be the biggest yet. Forty percent will be
earmarked for local consumption and the remainder for making
alcohol. 
</P>
