<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras Asks Mexico to Eliminate Tariffs on Meat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Honduran government has
formally requested Mexico to eliminate its tariffs on meat imports.
</P>
<P>
Honduras's Economy and Livestock Ministry presented the request
since the farmers in the country believe they are receiving
prejudicial treatment with the current rate of 25 percent imposed
by Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran proposal is to have the tariff on the beef it
sells to Mexico eliminated completely within the framework of the
bilateral negotiations over free trade.
</P>
<P>
Honduras, Guatemala and El Salvador, which make up the Group of
three (CA-3), have been negotiating a free trade agreement with
Mexico for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
In the last four years, a kilogram of meat has dropped from 1.3
U.S. dollars to 75 cents in the U.S. market which is the principal
market for this Honduran product. That is why Honduras is turning
to the Mexican market as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
Meat and sugar, both items which Mexico has in excess, are
among the products that would be considered in the CA-3
negotiations with that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Colombian exports
reached 3.5447 billion dollars during the first 4 months of this
year, an increase of 5.8 percent over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Traditional exports increased 9.86 percent in volume and 13.07
percent in value during the above-mentioned period, according to
the monthly report from the National Statistics Administrative
Department (DANE, its acronym in Spanish).
</P>
<P>
During this period, overseas sales of coffee, petroleum and
petroleum derivatives had the most outstanding performance with
increases of 27 and 6.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Coal exports increased 9.33 percent between January and April,
less than the 50 percent during the same period in 1996. Growth
in the first 4 months was higher than the 3.36 percent reported
during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports decreased 1.21 percent, dropping from
1.7109 billion dollars between January-April last year to 1.6902
billion dollars during the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the European Union and the Andean Group were
the main markets, together acquiring 77.9 percent of Colombia's
exports during the first 4 months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
