<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Agrees To Pay UN Official Salary Under </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Australia has agreed reluctantly
to pay an annual salary of 208,339 US dollars for two years to its
former U.N. Ambassador Richard Butler, who now heads the special
UN commission in charge of ridding Iraq of weapons of mass
destruction, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer is understood to have ordered
the salary payment following direct pressure from US Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and Britain's High Commissioner to
Australia Roger Carrick, the Australian Financial Review reported.
</P>
<P>
Downer and his department were angry over the payment, but felt
they had no choice but to agree when told that the Swedish
government had already paid the salary of Butler's Swedish
predecessor Rolf Ekeus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain warned Australia that the future
effectiveness of the U.N. commission could be put in doubt if the
issue of its chief's salary was re-opened in the U.N. Security
Council. They were concerned Russia would oppose the U.N. paying
the salary and that pressure on Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
would be weakened.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the foreign minister is understood to have
complained bitterly that Australia was not warned it would be
expected to pay the salary at the time the U.N. asked him to
release Butler to take up the appointment as head of the U.N.
commission.
</P>
<P>
Bulter retired from his post as Australia's U.N. ambassador to
head the commission following Australia's defeat last year in the
U.N. election for a seat on the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Butler is believed to have advised Australia's Department of
Foreign Affairs in May that he was retiring and The department
assumed he would be off its payroll when he became head of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Australia had protested strenuously when advised that Australia
would be expected to pay his salary following the Swedish
precedent, arguing that the U.N. should pay the salary to preserve
the independence of his office.
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, Albright telephoned Downer and said Australia
should be honored that Butler had been appointed to the
prestigious post and should meet his salary costs, the newspaper
quoted its unidentified sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Carrick, Britain's top diplomat to Australia, called on Downer
to voice Anglo-American concerns about the possibility of Russian
resistance if the question was taken back to the security council.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic's Foreign Exchange Reserves Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's foreign
exchange reserves dropped to 14.47 billion U.S. dollars by the end
of May, a dip of three billion dollars since the end of 1996,
according to a spokesman for the Finance Ministry here today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman attributed the reduction of foreign reserves to
the slow growth of the economy, an unbalanced state budget, heavy
deficit, unfavorable foreign trade and a weak currency.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of increasing foreign exchange reserves, the
country has taken steps to increase financial revenues and save on
expenditure, while seeking international loans.
</P>
<P>
On June 20, the country got low-interest loans totaling two
billion U.S. dollars from 24 international financial
organizations, with a year to repay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
