<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America's Foreign Debt Grows: SELA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The foreign debt of Latin American
and the Caribbean countries has increased by 873 percent over the
past 21 years and has become the most serious financial problem of
the region, says the Latin American Economic System (SELA).
</P>
<P>
The debt climbed from 69.93 billion U.S. dollars in 1975 to
603.43 billion dollars in 1996, said SELA in a report, presented
today before nearly 100 parliamentarians of the region. They were
attending a seminar in Caracas on the advances in integration and
on international economics.
</P>
<P>
The SELA pointed out that debtor countries could now improve
their negotiated conditions by exerting pressure against
multilateral forums such as the Club of Paris, or through the
strategy of repurchasing its foreign debt at market prices.
</P>
<P>
The organization believed that the changes in attitude of
developed countries and multilateral organizations, and the
increase in international liquidity, would create a "new situation
with respect to the foreign debt that would permit new proposals
of the issue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Maps Out Ethnic Health Care by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The central government is beefing
up its efforts to provide better health care for the more than 90
million ethnic people by 2000, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are urged to give priority to ethnic health
work and give support in policy-making and budget arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Ministry of Health suggested the ethnic
population has experienced great improvements in health in the
past with life expectancy prolonged from less than 30 in 1949 to
more than 65 years now.
</P>
<P>
More than 77 percent of the villages in ethnic areas have built
clinics. The incidence of infectious diseases, which used to be a
major threat to ethnic people, has been reduced to the national
average.
</P>
<P>
Many ethnic medical workers have been sent to developed
provinces for professional training.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the Ministry of Health and some provincial
governments have assigned 19 groups of health professionals from
hospitals in major cities to support health development in Tibet
and donated 6.3 million yuan (759,000 US dollars) worth of medical
instruments to Tibetan medical institutes.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the shortage of input and lack of high-quality
professionals remain major challenges for health development in
ethnic-inhabited areas, a Ministry of Health official said.
</P>
<P>
Many of these districts are economically backward, and cannot
afford to build medical institutions and improve facilities. It
also affects staff training and implementing disease control
projects, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Due to impacts from the environment and improper living
customs, the control of infectious and endemic diseases as well as
congenital ailments is an arduous task in ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
Because the number of elderly people is increasing, the regions
also face challenges from non-infectious chronic ailments such as
tumors and diabetes, said the Ministry of Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
