<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson's License Is Stripped, Fined 3 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson was banned from the
rings when his boxing license was revoked and was fined three
million U.S. dollars Wednesday for biting a chunk out of Evander
Holyfield's right ear during their June 28 WBA heavyweight title
fight.
</P>
<P>
Tyson can apply for reinstatement in one year, but officials
with the Nevada State Athletic Commission in Las Vegas said
there's no guarantee he could get his license back.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the commission changes its mind, this would be a
permanent revocation," the commission's legal adviser Donald
Haight said.
</P>
<P>
All other states are required by a new federal law to honor the
Nevada decision. And since Tyson is still on probation for his
1992 rape conviction, he might not get permission to leave the
country to fight overseas.
</P>
<P>
But Tyson's corner was optimistic about his chances of
returning to the ring.
</P>
<P>
"When everything's cooled down and the world is thinking about
other things, I feel very, very confident you'll see Mike Tyson
fighting again within a year," said Oscar Goodman, the boxer's
chief lawyer.
</P>
<P>
Tyson apologized on television last week and asked to be
allowed to fight again someday, but he did not show up at
Wednesday's hearing before the commission, leaving his lawyer to
plead his case.
</P>
<P>
The commission could have suspended Tyson for up to five years,
but state prosecutors argued for a stronger punishment. A
suspension would have allowed boxing regulators to fine Tyson a
maximum of 250,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
