<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Vegetables Fill HK Dishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong's vegetable suppliers
have consolidated their foothold in Hong Kong, thanks to the
efforts of the Guangdong Import and Export Commodity Inspection
Bureau (GDCIB), today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The province exports about 250,000 tons of vegetables to Hong
Kong annually, accounting for about 80 percent of China's total
and making up around 80 percent of Hong Kong's market needs.
</P>
<P>
GDCIB vice-president Zhan Siming said apart from the climate,
which is beneficial to vegetable growing, and Guangdong's
favorable geographical location, the measures taken by GDCIB to
ensure safety, hygiene and the punctual delivery of vegetables
also contribute significantly to exports.
</P>
<P>
Zhan said to guarantee the safety and hygiene of the
vegetables, GDCIB has laid down several regulations, including the
Provincial Hygiene Quality Examination and Inspection
Administration Temporary Regulations for Fresh Vegetables Exported
to Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Such regulations provide clear and concise guidelines for the
labelling system, the responsibilities borne by vegetable growers
and collectors, and even the dosages of pesticide.
</P>
<P>
And GDCIB has offered 11 terms' worth of courses for more than
300 vegetable growing and collection supervisors to make sure that
inspection covers every detail of vegetable growing and
processing.
</P>
<P>
GDCIB has purchased advanced instruments and facilities worth
more than 50 million yuan to strengthen the quality inspection
work on vegetables sent to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Research has also been applied advanced facilities to vegetable
examination to speed up the delivery of vegetables destined for
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, GDCIB has been co-operating with its
counterpart in Hong Kong to crack down on illegal vegetable
exports to Hong Kong. GDCIB compares notes with its counterpart in
Hong Kong twice a year.
</P>
<P>
The measures GDCIB has taken have benefited both Hong Kong
residents and the province's vegetable growers, Zhan said, as Hong
Kong residents can feel free to enjoy the vegetables from
Guangdong and the province's vegetable growers can make handsome
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Boosts Bicycle Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, has exported 713,000 bicycles so far this year,
an increase of about 27 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bicycles are valued at 30.3 million US dollars, up 37
percent, according to local customs statistics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has exported bicycle spare parts worth
12.7 million US dollars, up 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bicycles have been a major hard currency earner in Shanghai's
light industry sector. The export markets are mainly in Asian and
African countries, including Japan and Indonesia. More than 60
percent of Shanghai's bicycles have been exported to Japan this
year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the export rise to the high quality and low
prices of Shanghai's bicycles. In addition, more business
operations by Japanese and Taiwanese bicycle manufacturers has
also promoted exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
