<HEADLINE> Britain Sends 500 Troops to N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The British government is sending
500 more troops to Northern Ireland today to strengthen its forces
there in fighting a tide of nationalist violence which swept the
province since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The extra troops, which will arrive at the province within two
days, will help the local Royal Ulster Constabulary police "combat
terrorism and ensure law and order," local reports quoted an army
spokesman as saying. Over 18,000 British soldiers are already
serving in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
The continued violence was sparked off Sunday morning after
pro-British Protestants marched through a Catholic area in
Portadown in Northern Ireland with consent from the British
government.
</P>
<P>
The Protestants and anti-British Catholics remain intransigent
in a compromise over further parades scheduled for this weekend,
with tension remaining high in the province.
</P>
<P>
The Protestant Orange Order in Londonderry said it would not
change its plans for a march through the province's second city
Saturday despite objections from Catholics there.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's parade is the first by the Orange Order in
Londonderry for five years. Upwards of 10,000 Orangemen are
expected to take part.
</P>
<P>
July 12 marks the anniversary of a 1690 Protestant battle
victory over an invading Catholic king and is seen by Catholics as
an anachronistic display of triumphalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
