<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on Cypriot Parties to Negotiate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today called on leaders of both Cypriot communities to enter
upon a process of negotiations, leading to incremental
construction of the juridical framework to forge a new partnership
between the Greek Cypriot and the Turkish Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the opening of the Cyprus talks at the
Troutbeck conference center in Dutchess County, New York, Annan
said that through negotiations, leaders of the Cypriot communities
would be able to promote an increasingly fruitful convergence of
views and positions.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the negotiation process is under way, you will find
that it is the most practical way of formulating texts that are
mutually acceptable, and for that reason effective and durable,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the process will be conducted under the auspices
of the United Nations will add another dimension. It will ensure
that the principles of the Charter will inspire all the good
offices efforts of the secretary-general; will guide your
deliberations; and underlie all the understandings that you will
reach," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reviewed that the search for a peaceful solution to the
Cyprus problem had dragged on for too long.
</P>
<P>
"For 33 years and fourth months, the United Nations has toiled,
so far in vain, to bring about an agreed settlement. There have
been dozens of Security Council resolutions. Four
secretaries-general have worked hard to implement the council's
mandate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP),
originally set up for a period of three months, was still in
existence. The work of the UNFICYP had been invaluable in reducing
tension and containing the conflict. It had not been cost-free:
168 UN peacekeepers had paid the supreme price for peace on Cyprus
in addition to the UNFICYP's current annual cost of 50 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Today, international backing for a solution to the Cyprus issue
was firmer than ever. The support of the Security Council had been
unequivocal. This meeting itself -- and the presence of special
envoys from so many countries -- was proof of the high priority
the international community attached to the search for a viable
and comprehensive solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us, therefore, press forward, in a positive spirit, in
search of our common goal, a viable and comprehensive solution to
the Cyprus problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
By reaching agreement, the Cypriot communities would not only
earn the respect and gratitude of the international community,
they would also earn its profound relief at the removal of a
potential flashpoint from international relations in the eastern
Mediterranean and, most important, provide a prosperous and
peaceful future for all Cypriots, he said in conclusion.
</P>
<P>
The first round of Cyprus talks has been attended by
representatives from Finland, Germany, China, Russia, France and
10 other countries and senior UN officials in addition to leaders
of the two Cypriot communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Need Sex Education, Family Planning: UNFPA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Young people from throughout
the world articulated their need for accurate information on sex,
AIDS, family planning services, and their desire to marry and have
children later in life, according to the United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA).
</P>
<P>
In a new publication, the UNFPA noted that young people also
wanted their parents' help in all this but they did not want to be
pressured or controlled by them. Instead, they were looking
forward for support and guidance as they made their transition to
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
The Youth Perspective, the UNFPA booklet, contains writings
from an essay contest sponsored by the Fund on the theme of
"promoting responsible reproductive behavior."
</P>
<P>
"In this booklet, young people speak from the heart and with
great passion," said Nafis Sadik, UNFPA executive director. "They
tell us they want sexual education and information on reproductive
health, preferably from their parents. They want this information
early and in a form appropriate to their psychological and
physical development. They want accurate information so they can
empower themselves to make choices and take responsibility for
those choices."
</P>
<P>
She said that many of the young writers indicated they wanted
to have family planning information and supplies that would allow
them to avoid early and unwanted pregnancy, and abortion, and to
protect themselves from sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Sadik also said that one of the key themes of the booklet was
an abhorrence of sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The booklet contains essays, in part and whole, from a contest
organized in 1996 by the UNFPA to give voice to young people and
to assist the Fund in its work with adolescents, especially in the
areas of sex education and information. There were 17 winners of
the contest, aged 14 to 23, chosen by UNFPA judges from more than
500 entries from 107 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government to Resume Talks with Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Hassan
al-Bashir announced today that his government will soon resume
peace talks with southern rebels in a bid to end the 14-year
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
However, there will be no face-to-face talks between Bashir
and John Garang, the leader of the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), Sudanese Deputy Ambassador Elsadig Osman
said. Garang also ruled out such a possibility here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sixth Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD)
summit ending earlier today has paved the way for the forthcoming
talks between the Islamist-backed Sudanese government and the
SPLA, Bashir said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day summit, Bashir turned about and accepted the
Declaration of Principles, which was drafted by IGAD leaders in
1994 but then had been rejected by Khartoum, as the basis of
talks to end the conflicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
His move was hailed by leaders of other IGAD member states
attending the summit -- Presidents Daniel arap Moi of Kenya,
Hassan Aptidon of Djibouti and Isaias Afwerki of Eritrea,
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and Ugandan First Deputy
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Eriya Kategaya.
</P>
<P>
"The summit considered this development a major breakthrough
in the peace initiative," said the leaders in a joint communique.
</P>
<P>
"This will enable the parties to the conflict to freely
discuss and negotiate on all the points enshrined in the
declaration of principles," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Bashir and SPLA leader John Garang
mediated by IGAD nations broke down in 1994 when the Sudanese
government refused to sign the declaration of principles.
</P>
<P>
The declaration recognized religious factor as an important
role in Sudan's development, saying religion and the state are
separate, and endorsed self-determination for Sudan's Christian
south.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has fought in southern Sudan since 1983 for greater
autonomy of the Christian south from the Moslem north and now is
allied with armed opposition groups in northern Sudan with
battles continuing both in the north and in the south.
</P>
<P>
"In order to break the impasse, the talks must be resumed by
all parties in the conflict so that a lasting solution can be
found," Moi vowed in his opening speech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD held two high-level meetings in 1994 on the crisis in
Sudan but the talks were deadlocked. Since then, all IGAD peace
initiative has stalled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leaders expressed satisfaction that "the
situation in northern Somalia was relatively stable and urged
cooperation among the factions in order to create a united and
peaceful Somalia," according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's chair is vacant at the seven-member IGAD summit as
usual because it has not had a central government since 1991 when
clan leaders joined hands to oust former leader Mohamed Siad
Barre and then sent the Horn of African country into war-torn
situation.
</P>
<P>
IGAD was set up in 1986 for enhancing cooperation on
anti-drought and economic development among the member countries.
Regional political affairs have been on its agenda since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD member states have "resolved to strengthen IGAD
through prompt payment of assessed contributions" and "redouble
their efforts in providing the necessary resources for
infrastructure development," said the communique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
