<HEADLINE> Mubarak Issues Decree on Governorates Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Egypt changed some of its
governorates a day after the cabinet has a limited shake-up, in a
drive to speed up the country's economic development, the Middle
East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a republican decree issued by President Hosni Mubarak today,
the governors reshuffle has introduced 10 new-comers, changed the
places of four others and kept 12 in their seats.
</P>
<P>
The new governors will take oaths before the president
Thursday, a day after 10 newly-appointed ministers were sworn in.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's limited cabinet reshuffle, which took place 18 months
after Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri took office on January 2nd,
1996, also introduced a new ministry of rural development.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 newly-appointed ministers, four of them were new
blood while the other six merely assumed new ministerial
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
The shake-up is aimed at giving a boost to the efficiency in
the government, according to el-Ganzouri who made the new
nominations Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
"The present stage requires speed and decisiveness in
performance in various domains of production and services,"
Ganzouri told reporters after the swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In the shake-up, some ministries were split up to create new
ones like ministries of environment and higher education. The
philosophy behind the move is to enhance performance, according to
the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Most of the outgoing ministers are those in charge of public
