<HEADLINE> Mugabe Cautions Workers Against Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today cautioned workers countrywide not to resort to strikes
without pursuing collective bargaining channels in their quest
for higher wages this year.
</P>
<P>
''Workers should not succumb to the sense of indiscipline.
Arguments should be presented well and not rush into strikes
because they have an adverse effect if they become the only
resort to failed negotiations,'' Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of workers in the construction, clothing and textile
industries downed their tools Tuesday, demanding salary rise
which management failed to meet.
</P>
<P>
The strikes followed others staged by hotel and restaurant
workers countrywide which paralyzed tourism services for more
than three days.
</P>
<P>
Employees of the recently commercialized posts and
telecommunications corporation began a go-slow last Friday
demanding 40 percent salary increase, while thousands of
employees of the national railways of Zimbabwe downed their tools
demanding more than 50 percent rise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, threats of more strikes continue with bank workers
warning they could go into the streets Thursday.
</P>
<P>
''The strikes have a double effect,'' Mugabe said, adding,
''they affect the viability of the company, and, in the long
term, affects the prosperity of the workers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
