<HEADLINE> S. Leone Soldiers Trade Fire With Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A combined unit of the Sierra
Leone army and the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) traded heavy
artillery fire today with Nigerian troops around the country's
international airport, military sources said.
</P>
<P>
The assault which began at around 11.30 am sent thousands of
civilians in nearby villages fleeing to Port Loko town, about 30
miles away, local reporters on the scene said.
</P>
<P>
Military officials in Freetown said there were mild damages to
the airport itself and that up to about 10 Nigerian soldiers may
have been either wounded or killed.
</P>
<P>
They described their own casualties as light. But there has
not been any independent confirmation about the claim.
</P>
<P>
According to residents near the airport, a column of combined
Sierra Leone and RUF troops were on their way to the airport when
an argument ensued between them and Nigerian troops.
</P>
<P>
''The Nigerians were hostile and started trading insults and
then things got out of hand,'' a military official said.
</P>
<P>
''There was a near hand-to-hand fighting at one stage before
the two sides separated and took up heavy bombardment," the
official reported.
BBH209NBB168I09TSQL01:2001:211732
</P>
<P>
Two gun boats belonging to the Sierra Leone navy which were
patrolling the seafront, also took part in the battle.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment was heard in the capital across the Sierra
Leone River and it sent hundreds of civilians scurrying for
safety. Shops and markets were closed and a number of accidents
were reported as motorists raced for safety.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources said they believed that the Sierra Leone
soldiers were out to scale down the presence of Nigerian soldiers
at the airport where they had formed a blockade against any
civilian flights arriving in the country for the past six weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
