<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Immunize 8 Million Children Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Health Ministry said today
it has plans to immunize 8.5 million children in Ethiopia against
polio in the current fiscal year beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Mekonnen Admassu, expert from the ministry said at a
workshop here that 8.5 million children aged below five will be
inoculated in November and December against the disease.
</P>
<P>
He said, only 260,000, representing two percent of the
children in the country, were inoculated against polio during the
just ended 1996/97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, doctor Wedson C. Mwambazi, representative of the
World Health Organization (WHO) in Ethiopia, said at the workshop
that the world health assembly decided in 1990 to include polio-
myelitis on the list of targeted diseases for eradication.
</P>
<P>
He said in 1995 about 74 percent of WHO's member states were
polio free while Ethiopia is among the remaining 26 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
