<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Appoints 17-Member Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Sierra Leone's military
junta Major Johnny Koroma appointed a 17-member cabinet late
Tuesday, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet is head by Koroma who is also Commander in
Chief of the Armed Forces and Defense Minister.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the ex-rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
Corporal Foday Sankoh, who is reportedly detained in Nigeria, was
appointed the deputy Head of State.
</P>
<P>
Former number two in the military regime between 1992 and
1996, retired Captain Saj Musa became Chief Secretary of State
and Minister of Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
The new Foreign Secretary is Paulo Bangura, Sierra Leone's
one-time Ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Two lawyers, Oladipo Robbin Mason and Osho Williams, were
appointed Attorney General and Transport and Communications
Minister respectively.
</P>
<P>
A former finance minister in the civilian government of Joseph
Momoh in 1990, Joe Amara Bangali was re-appointed while a key
minister in the military regime of 1991, Victor Brandon, was
named as Secretary of Development and Planning.
</P>
<P>
Two women were in the cabinet, with Kula Samba as Secretary
for Social Welfare and Gender Affairs, and Shirley Rogers Wright,
for Education.
</P>
<P>
The State Radio also announced the appointment of 12
under-secretaries and a 30-man armed forces council with Koroma
as its leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
