<HEADLINE> German Insurer Warns Business Against Insider Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A leading German insurance company
today warned companies against the increasing danger of
embezzlement by their own staff, saying that it would cost them
HAB263HAB272i0709QU02:0202:020123
some 10 billion marks (5.7 billion U.S. dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hermes Kreditversicherung, which provides
insurance against fraud, Germany registered last year about
750,000 cases of embezzlement committed by a company's own staff
with losses totaling at 9.3 billion marks (5.3 billion dollars).
This year the figure might top 800,000 cases, it added.
</P>
<P>
The insurance company believes that the steady growth in such
crimes results from the rising indebtedness of German households,
a collapse in corporate values, as well as companies's structural
changes such as lean management and rationalization through more
use of computers.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the threat of punishment will not be enough,
instead the companies should take necessary precautions. 
</P>
