<HEADLINE> First Kuwaiti Plane in 7 Years Lands in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The first Kuwaiti commercial plane
landed here today after a break of seven years, following an
agreement signed between Jordan and Kuwait last month.
</P>
<P>
This was "another demonstration of the improved relationship
between the two countries," Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus A320 flight of Kuwait Airways Corporation (KAC),
carrying 170 passengers, was welcomed at Jordanian Queen Alia
International Airport by Jordanian Civil Aviation Authority (JCAA)
staff members and Kuwaiti diplomats.
</P>
<P>
From today, KAC starts its regular semi-weekly flights, on every
Wednesday and Friday, from Kuwait to Amman.
</P>
<P>
Captain Jarsad Ziyad, JCAA director, told reporters that he
hoped the number of flights would increase. He described the first
flight as a "good start."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti diplomat Fizad Mohaisen told reporters that this would
contribute to enhancing ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Royal Jordanian (RJ) company will start the first
of its semi-weekly flights, on every Monday and Thursday, from
Amman to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The schedule was set last month when both sides agreed that
their national air carriers should resume flights following a
hiatus of seven years.
</P>
<P>
The two airlines suspended flights following 1990's Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has not restored full diplomatic ties with Jordan, which
has been seen as sympathizing with Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
