<HEADLINE> Russia Repeats Opposition to NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry today
once again reiterated its position against the NATO's eastwards
expansion, alleging the NATO enlargement is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a briefing here, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady
Tarasov criticized the NATO leaders, who is holding summit in
Madrid, for the decision to invite three East European countries
to the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision runs counter to the task of creating a
single security space in the Euro-Atlantic area."NATO expansion
will sooner create new problems than it will resolve existing
ones", Tarasov added.
</P>
<P>
All countries in the Euro-Atlantic area, the spokesman said,
should have equal security guarantees irrespective of their
membership in military and political alliances.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov noted Discussion of NATO enlargement has, and will
have, a negative impact on the general political situation in
Europe. He said "there is no doubt that what we need now is not
discussions about NATO candidates of the first or second wave, but
efforts aimed at strengthening stability and security in Europe."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed anxiety about the indirect mention
of the Baltic states in the Madrid Declaration in the context of
NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"For us this decision was and remains unacceptable," Tarasov
said, "however, we are ready to discuss a system of security
guarantees which Russia and other countries or international
organizations could give the Baltic states."
YPR151CAB090I09TAQL03:2403:260885
S23151CAB090I09TAQL03:2403:260885
S25151CAB090I09TAQL03:2403:260885
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he welcomed the fact that in their Declaration the
NATO member-states confirmed their intention to continue efforts
within the framework of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to work out a comprehensive security model
for Europe in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Russia also welcomes NATO's determination to comply with all
the provisions of the Founding Act between Russia and NATO.
</P>
