<HEADLINE> MIR Space Station Suffers Ongoing Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The troubles suffered by Russia's
Mir space station make it much harder for a Russian space industry
already battered by market reforms to attract investments, Russian
Space agency deputy director Yuri Milov told a briefing here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Recent foreign investments have mostly gone toward construction
of the Alpha international space station anyway, Milov said.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, funding is not likely to fall sharply either, he
said and believed the project would materialize.
</P>
<P>
NASA responded with sympathy to the crash of a progress cargo
craft into a Mir station module June 25, depressurizing it and
attached to the damaged module, the space official said.
</P>
<P>
NASA professionals know that if one plane crashed, this does
not mean that all flights should stop, Milov said.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the first fatal accident involving astronauts
occurred in the United States, but that did not bring an end to
the U.S. manned space program.
</P>
<P>
Milov said the situation on board Mir is improving and the
consequences of the crash will be dealt with shortly. 
</P>
