<HEADLINE> 1997 German Budget Foresees 71 Bln Marks in New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The German government is expecting a
new borrowing of 71.2 billion marks (40.9 billion U.S. dollars)
for its 1997 budget, 17.9 billion marks (10.3 billion dollars)
higher than foreseen at the end of last year, said media reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Under Bonn's revised budget for 1997, government expenditures
would increase by 18.7 billion marks (10.7 billion dollars) to
458.6 billion (263.6 billion dollars), the German news agency DPA
quoted government sources as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one third of the spendings, or 149.06 billion marks
(85.7 billion dollars), would be used to cover the increasing
social welfare costs for the country's large army of jobless
people which now stands at nearly 4.4 million, or a rate of 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
Under a separate draft budget for 1998, government expenditures
are expected to increase by 0.5 percent to 461 billion marks
(264.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of an improvement on the job market, the labor
and social affairs spendings would be reduced by 1.3 percent from
the level of 1997, to 147.06 billion marks (84.5 billion dollars),
but would still remain the largest budget item.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to cuts across the board elsewhere, the 1998
defense budget, the second largest item, would increase by 0.8
percent to 46.67 billion marks (26.8 billion dollars) when
compared with 1997. Among them 850 million marks (488.5 million
dollars) would be earmarked to fund the Eurofighter jet to ensure
that the four-European-nation joint warplane project can go ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
