<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Re-consider Arms Sale to Rwanda: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 9 (Xinhua)-- South Africa will reconsider
its arms sales to Rwanda, which was suspended in November last
year, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned that the government of Rwanda should have
the capacity to protect itself against attacks," Mbeki told
reporters after meeting his Rwandan counterpart Paul Kagame in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
According to Mbeki, some refugees returning to Rwanda were
from the old militia in that country. "They come back with their
guns and resume some of the military conflict."
</P>
<P>
This was affecting the work of aid organizations and
non-government bodies helping to resettle refugees. The matter
had also been raised by the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa suspended its arms sale to Rwanda in November
last year, pending the return of the stability to the central
African region. The decision was taken after indications showed
that the Rwandan armed forces made cross-border incursions into
former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
South Africa said at that time that the suspension would be
reviewed once cross-border violations by Rwanda ceased and a
clear understanding emerged that its armed forces were using
weapons for self-defense only.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Kagame's visit, Mbeki said South Africa and
Rwanda would sign a memorandum of understanding on general
cooperation during Kagame's visit.
</P>
<P>
Technical task teams would then examine ways in which South
Africa could aid reconstruction in Rwanda. The private sector
would also be involved, Mbeki said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
