<HEADLINE> World Bank Funds Water Projects in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Construction of two multi-million
U.S. Dollars water supply projects financed by the World Bank is
in full swing in northern Nigeria, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The first multi-stage water supply project in Kaduna State is
expected to be completed in July next year, while that in Katsina
State is projected to be finished in mid 1999.
</P>
<P>
A report by a World Bank visiting group said today that the
two projects which started in 1993 are financed entirely by the
bank's credit scheme of about 101 million U.S. Dollars, with
local funding largely from the state governments.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Kaduna project, involving both
urban and rural water supply schemes at a cost of about 53
million Dollars, will provide additional 31,000 cubic meters of
potable water daily when completed.
</P>
<P>
The Katsina project, also involving urban and rural water
supply systems, will cost some 59 million Dollars and is targeted
at an additional potable water supply of 58,500 cubic meters a
day.
</P>
<P>
Local communities, the beneficiaries of the projects, will be
mobilized to contribute a small proportion of the capital costs
and be responsible for operating and maintaining the schemes, it
said. 
</P>
