<HEADLINE> US to Evacuate Part of Embassy Staff in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department said
today the Clinton administration is ordering 41 diplomats and
their dependents out of Cambodia because of the uncertain security
situation there.
</P>
<P>
The staff at the embassy in Phnom Penh would be reduced to 20
after the other 41 leave the country, but it would keep the
mission open, spokesman Nicholas Burns told a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Although the Pentagon had made contingency plans for a possible
military evacuation, it was hoped the diplomats and their
dependents could leave by civilian transport now that flights were
being restored at the Phnom Penh airport, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
He also said Americans in the country, estimated at 1,000 to
1,300, were urged to leave Cambodia over the next few days, even
though "the situation in Phnom Penh is quieter than it has been at
any time over the last four or five days." There still was
sporadic shooting in the capital and in other places.
</P>
<P>
Burns disclosed that Cambodia's First Prime Minister Prince
Norodom Ranariddh was on his way to the United States from France
for meetings with U.N. officials in New York and would probably
meet Friday with Acting Secretary of State Thomas Pickering, who
is standing in while Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is in
Madrid attending a NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
They might discuss whether to suspend a 42 million U.S. aid
program for Cambodia, given the political situation in the
Southeast Asian country. 
</P>
