<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Leaders Start Talks Near New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash met today for the first
time in nearly three years to search for ways for a peaceful
solution to the long-standing Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, expected to last five days, took place at a rural
resort called Troutbeck, some 90 miles north of New York.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials hope that the isolated setting will encourage
the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities to search
for an end to the 23-year division of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"The search for a peaceful solution to the Cyprus problem has
dragged on for too long," said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
who presided over the opening session of the talks.
</P>
<P>
"This is a place where I'm sure cool minds and clear heads will
prevail," the U.N. chief added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been virtually partitioned since troops from Turkey
took over the north of the island in 1974 in reaction to a coup in
Nicosia backed by the junta then ruling Greece.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been trying for decades to reunite the
Mediterranean island nation as a bi-communal, bi-zonal federation.
</P>
<P>
No agreements are expected from this fresh round of
U.N-sponsored talks of the leaders of the Greek and Cypriot
communities. Instead, U.N. officials hope that the two sides will
agree to meet again next month. U.N. officials hold out little
hope for major developments until the Greek Cypriots hold their
presidential elections next February.
</P>
<P>
Clerdies told reporters that he came to talk with Denktash
"with the intention of negotiating seriously."
</P>
<P>
"If the other side is prepared to do that, then I will become
an optimist," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader also stressed his good intention for
talks. But he said that the Turkish Cypriots will be looking for
signs that the Greek Cypriots, who make up 80 percent of the
island's population, are willing to accept Turks as equals in a
"bizonal" state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970710.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Between Warring Factions Postponed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman from the mayor of
Congolese capital Brazzaville said the peace talks between the
Congolese president Pascal Lissouba's troops and the militia
loyal to former president Sassou Nguesso was postponed, sources
monitored said here today.
</P>
<P>
According to mayor Bernard Kolelas's spokesman, the
postponement was blamed on the dispute about who should sign a
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the two warring sides planned to be
held today was proposed by the mediation committee led by Bernard
Kolelas, the mayor of Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in Brazzaville began last month. Mediation
efforts had been made soon after the conflict erupted but no
success yet.
</P>
<P>
Reports say an African peace keeping force directed by Senegal
is being set up. The first contingent of some 500 men is expected
in Brazzaville soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
