<HEADLINE> Philip Morris, Top Soft Money Donor for US Election: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Philip Morris, a trans-national
tobacco giant, was the single biggest political soft money donor
during the 1996 presidential election, a watch-dog group reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Common Cause said that Philip Morris gave
at least 2.5 million U.S. dollars to various Republican Party
committees and nearly half a million U.S. dollars to Democratic
Party committees.
</P>
<P>
Soft money refers to those donated outside the limits of
federal campaign spending laws to political parties and their
committees but not to individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Common Cause said that the Democratic and Republican
parties raised more than 260 million U.S. dollars in soft money
during the last election cycle starting from January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Besides Philip Morris, top soft money donors for the
Republicans include American Financial Group, Atlantic Richfield,
News Corporation, RJR Nabisco and Union Pacific Corp/Southern
Pacific Corp.
</P>
<P>
The biggest soft money donor for the Democrats was Joseph E
Seagram &AMP; Sons Inc/MCA Inc, a liquorats and media concern. It gave
1.18 million U.S. dollars to the party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
