<HEADLINE> IGAD Seeks Peaceful Solutions to Somalia, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-Governmental
Authority for Development (IGAD) today said it is committed to
seeking peaceful solutions to the crises of Somalia and Sudan at
the end of a two-day summit meeting in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD summit pledged unreserved support to bring peace and
reconciliation in Somalia and help in building the war-torn
economy of the Horn of Africa country, according to Ethiopian
Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here accompanying Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
who has attended the summit, Seyoum said this evening that the
summit has expressed its concern over the situation in Somalia
and underlined that joint efforts will be launched to bring about
peace in that country.
</P>
<P>
Regarding to the Sudan problem, the minister said, the summit
has expressed satisfaction over Sudan's acceptance of the
declaration of principles as the basis for discussions and
negotiations between conflicting parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the summit considers this development as a major
breakthrough in the peace initiative," adding that Sudan's
acceptance of the declaration would enable the parties to the
conflict to freely discuss and negotiate on points enshrined in
the declaration.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum also said the summit welcomed the decision of the OAU
to recognize the IGAD as a regional economic community.
</P>
<P>
The summit urged the IGAD's development partners to finance
projects in the priority areas and to redouble their efforts in
providing the necessary resources for infrastructure development,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
