<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges 120 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
flirted with the 8,000 mark, but plunged this afternoon on doubts
about guaranteed corporate profit forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The Dow lost 119.88 points to 7,842.43.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with the NYSE volume amounting to
589.08 million shares, much more than 525.65 million on the
Tuesday session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list was down 11.14 at 907.61.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was down 5.46 at 473.03. The American
Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.09 at 631.02.
</P>
<P>
Bucking the trend, the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index
was up 1.77 at 1,486.87, riding to a new record high.
</P>
<P>
After an opening rally that took the Dow above 7,990, the Dow
dropped as much as 167.38 in the final hour of trading. The drop
more than erased the previous day's record-setting 100-point gain.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the decline to program trading, investors
reaping profits from Tuesday's surge and fear that the previous
session's jump was unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
With no major economic data scheduled for this week until
Friday's reading on wholesale prices, the market is closely
watching earnings reports for signs of the pace of growth in the
just-ended second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
